[Amit Varma]: ask everything about food I don't want to do that people contain multitudes as

00:09:35.480 --> 00:09:38.960
[Amit Varma]: I like saying on the show to tell me about your childhood how was it growing

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:45.120
[Guest]: up in Bombay what was your family like so I was a 70s kid and I was born in

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:49.760
[Guest]: Bombay like you said and my three generations like right from my great

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:57.880
[Guest]: grandparents who had moved to Bombay in 1930s early 1930s and then of course my

00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:03.200
[Guest]: grandparents and my parents and then me so I'm like a though I'm Tamil but I'm

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:11.880
[Guest]: fourth generation Mumbiker and yeah so I was the first in my generation both from

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:16.680
[Guest]: my paternal side and the maternal side so both my parents being the eldest kids

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:22.760
[Guest]: I was the first in my generation while you know I was pampered a lot and like

00:10:22.760 --> 00:10:27.000
[Guest]: of course like the first child in any like a generation is always most

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:31.160
[Guest]: welcomed and it's the novelty like people are literally looking at diapers

00:10:31.160 --> 00:10:39.480
[Guest]: after 20 years you know so I also I was living with my grandparents my three

00:10:39.480 --> 00:10:44.120
[Guest]: maternal aunts and while my mom and dad were in the same city they both were

00:10:44.120 --> 00:10:47.720
[Guest]: working so I was brought up by my grandparents and my aunts essentially

00:10:47.720 --> 00:10:54.800
[Guest]: and my mom used to come over on weekends etc and we had this kind of different

00:10:54.800 --> 00:10:59.800
[Guest]: arrangement for those days because it was not very common but and I would have

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:04.040
[Guest]: a tough time explaining to friends like where is your mother how how do you have

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:09.720
[Guest]: five mothers like you know three aunts one mom and one grandmom strong feminine

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:14.480
[Guest]: influence around me and like where are your parents they hardly come for any

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:18.440
[Guest]: school days so that that was my childhood and I think over a period of

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:22.760
[Guest]: time I got used to answering those questions and dealing with that my my

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:26.600
[Guest]: life is different from other kids who live in these nuclear families just

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:31.840
[Guest]: parents and kids or a sibling and my sister is 10 years younger to me so for

00:11:31.840 --> 00:11:37.000
[Guest]: the longest time I was a single child all through my you know childhood and

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:42.680
[Guest]: that I think that also played a big role in shaping who I am today because one

00:11:42.680 --> 00:11:48.760
[Guest]: growing up with grandparents there is that kind of undeniable generation gap

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:53.320
[Guest]: where you want to do something and you know you are a bit wired then they don't

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:58.640
[Guest]: want they have very strict rules also being this you know Tamil family but

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:04.160
[Guest]: although even Bombay I think I had a more conservative upbringing than people

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:08.600
[Guest]: stories I hear about in tier 2 and tier 3 cities I think even their parents were

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:13.120
[Guest]: like a little more aspirational thing yeah be modern wear jeans you know have

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:19.960
[Guest]: boyfriends and stuff which it was never the case in my house is very strict so

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:24.920
[Guest]: going back to actually I want to go back to my great-grandparents moving to

00:12:24.920 --> 00:12:29.840
[Guest]: Bombay because that's the story I really like and you know I find it interesting

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:34.720
[Guest]: how did you guys just suddenly pack up and come here from you know Tamil Nadu

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:38.880
[Guest]: and I had the privilege of having my great-grandmother in my life even when

00:12:38.880 --> 00:12:44.160
[Guest]: my son was born so she's she lived to 85 86 so we actually have a five generation

00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:49.400
[Guest]: picture of my great-grandmother my grandmother my mother me and my son so

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:52.080
[Guest]: I was telling my son if you were a daughter we would we would have been

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:56.680
[Guest]: five generations of women together but yeah it's okay I'll be I won't complain

00:12:56.680 --> 00:13:02.720
[Guest]: yeah so my great-grandparents my great-grandfather moved to Bombay first

00:13:02.720 --> 00:13:07.280
[Guest]: to look for prospects and all he already had three daughters by then in in a

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:11.960
[Guest]: small town in Tamil Nadu and he came to Bombay because also he knew that a lot

00:13:11.960 --> 00:13:15.480
[Guest]: of people had migrated from there so he stayed with a cousin who lived near

00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:19.520
[Guest]: Ruia college somewhere he stayed like for a couple of months and he had

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:24.320
[Guest]: actually done MA in English and history so there was no way that he would find a

00:13:24.320 --> 00:13:29.600
[Guest]: job of any you know relevance in the small town in Tamil Nadu and he said okay

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:32.720
[Guest]: this is a good place for me to find look I'm looking for a job I have three

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:37.000
[Guest]: daughters to support and I need to do something with my life so he stayed in

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.560
[Guest]: this cousin's place for a month or two and then he got a job with Western

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:47.720
[Guest]: Railways and then the best option to find a place was Matunga or King Circle

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:51.360
[Guest]: because there was already the set community the people speaking your

00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:56.560
[Guest]: language you know the vegetable vendors selling your kind of subzis, temples so

00:13:56.560 --> 00:14:01.400
[Guest]: like that whole ecosystem was kind of set up for someone migrating to such a

00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:06.480
[Guest]: big city even in 1930s like Bombay was the kind of an intimidating city for

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:11.840
[Guest]: someone who's never been outside their village before so they found this small

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:17.960
[Guest]: apartment in King Circle and you know I often ask my mom and aunts about these

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:22.240
[Guest]: stories so they said that in those days this two rent board would be hanging

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:28.480
[Guest]: from the trees and outside the buildings and the rent was it was 1930s and the

00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:33.520
[Guest]: rent was around five rupees a month and my great-grandfather's salary in those

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:37.640
[Guest]: days was around 30 rupees and he had like three and he had three children to

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:43.800
[Guest]: support and pay the house rent and the school fees and everything right so the

00:14:43.800 --> 00:14:48.360
[Guest]: funny thing was that anytime that two rent board changed into like someone

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:52.120
[Guest]: offering even like a four rupee fifty paisa people would just pick up their

00:14:52.120 --> 00:14:56.680
[Guest]: stuff and move to the next possible house because there were hardly any

00:14:56.680 --> 00:15:01.080
[Guest]: furniture in those days hardly any possessions except for your cooking

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:07.000
[Guest]: utensils two three pairs of clothes and a sack of coal which was your supply to

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:12.560
[Guest]: run the kitchen for the month and that was all and my mom and my aunts tell me

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:16.320
[Guest]: that this was the situation in most families but surprisingly these guys

00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:20.520
[Guest]: never moved they stayed in the same apartment for over 50 years and even I

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:23.680
[Guest]: have been there and I have stayed there with them and I have good memories of

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:27.740
[Guest]: that place and I even after they moved out of that place I used to go back and

00:15:27.740 --> 00:15:32.320
[Guest]: hang around there just you know for the kicks of nostalgia and getting all

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:37.440
[Guest]: sentimental about the place where my family first came into Bombay so I asked

00:15:37.440 --> 00:15:42.620
[Guest]: my mom other than the cultural reason why Matunga and King Circle so she said

00:15:42.620 --> 00:15:47.120
[Guest]: in those days that was the cheaper kind of available option given the salary

00:15:47.120 --> 00:15:54.760
[Guest]: that Tata was earning and also that you know having a self-contained house with

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:59.480
[Guest]: a bathroom inside the house was also a very big deal in those days and those

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:05.440
[Guest]: houses were quite expensive to rent and this given that it was only five rupees

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:10.200
[Guest]: a month it was five rupees a month not only but it was still a good amount for

00:16:10.200 --> 00:16:13.520
[Guest]: having a bathroom in the house when you have three daughters and you have a

00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:17.760
[Guest]: bigger family you don't want to risk you know not having a bathroom in the house

00:16:17.760 --> 00:16:24.320
[Guest]: so that was the other reason and I found it like wow I mean you know it fills me

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:30.120
[Guest]: with the kind of feeling that I can't really explain how things were at that

00:16:30.120 --> 00:16:35.000
[Guest]: time and because I've lived so much with my grandparents I used to hear a lot of

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:41.120
[Guest]: stories from them about their times in early Bombay the one thing that I know

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:45.760
[Guest]: firsthand is that my mother's cousin brother who's also my great-grandparents

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:49.840
[Guest]: grandson he would often tell my great-grandparents that you guys you

00:16:49.840 --> 00:16:54.360
[Guest]: have lived in Matunga like for 50 years but you would never learn proper Hindi

00:16:54.360 --> 00:16:58.480
[Guest]: or Marathi and all the Sabzi Walas have learned Tamil and they call you when you

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:02.920
[Guest]: go buying vegetables that you know they will name all the vegetables in Tamil

00:17:02.920 --> 00:17:06.840
[Guest]: saying Amma you're not taking this vegetable today so that was like the

00:17:06.840 --> 00:17:12.160
[Guest]: standing joke in our family that how much of the Tamil culture they infused

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:18.040
[Guest]: into the UP people the Bihar people the Gujaratis like everybody just became a

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:22.320
[Guest]: part of that Tamil culture going to temples and everything just became part

00:17:22.320 --> 00:17:28.040
[Guest]: of their DNA purely because it was such a cultural hub of Tamilians in Bombay so

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:34.120
[Guest]: that's about my great-grandparents and then my grandfather had a government job

00:17:34.120 --> 00:17:39.440
[Guest]: and with the central government and so I was born in the house where he had a

00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:45.040
[Guest]: quarters in Napien Sea Road and it was this big beautiful house facing the

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:48.960
[Guest]: Arabian Sea and those days the Priyadarshani Park had not yet come up it

00:17:48.960 --> 00:17:54.680
[Guest]: came up just when we left that house so it was this unobstructed view of the

00:17:54.680 --> 00:17:59.600
[Guest]: sea and I was so spoilt I would say what is this every day I wake up I only see

00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:03.880
[Guest]: the sea view I mean little did I know that you know I would kill for such a

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:08.600
[Guest]: view later on in my life but talk about having something at your disposal every

00:18:08.600 --> 00:18:12.200
[Guest]: day and you don't have the value for that at all like especially in the

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:16.200
[Guest]: monsoons the you couldn't even open the balcony door because the winds would

00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:21.840
[Guest]: come howling inside and push the door back so those are the memories I have of

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:25.920
[Guest]: growing up in Napien Sea Road and I didn't know that this was literally the

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:30.040
[Guest]: creme de la creme area to live in Bombay for me yeah it was just a house and it

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:34.280
[Guest]: was just a place in Bombay I had no idea about the suburbs and you know the

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:38.680
[Guest]: different hierarchies it was fun it was like this huge quarters government

00:18:38.680 --> 00:18:43.640
[Guest]: quarters lots of families of you know different languages religions it was

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:48.200
[Guest]: like a melting pot and it was no longer just like a Tamil hub there was this

00:18:48.200 --> 00:18:53.960
[Guest]: temple and lots of friends to play with so that that that was the first ten

00:18:53.960 --> 00:18:58.920
[Guest]: years of my life and I attended school somewhere there near Chowpatty I was

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:02.800
[Guest]: always like quite a studious kid also because I didn't I was not a very

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:08.640
[Guest]: outdoorsy kid and I was not the one to be playing out all the time so my mostly

00:19:08.640 --> 00:19:14.440
[Guest]: I would be studying reading or learning music or mostly indoor kind of things to

00:19:14.440 --> 00:19:19.880
[Guest]: do and so then I would without much effort I would be in the top one two

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:23.880
[Guest]: three ranks in school I don't think anybody ever bothered about it in my

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:28.560
[Guest]: house they said yeah okay your exams you're studying and because my mom would

00:19:28.560 --> 00:19:33.040
[Guest]: sometimes come on the weekends before my exam to coach me on some asking do some

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:35.760
[Guest]: mock test and all with me because they said what is this girl doing nobody

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:40.080
[Guest]: knows whether she's studying or not studying so just to keep a little bit of

00:19:40.080 --> 00:19:45.160
[Guest]: a watch on me and we would do these things I don't know am I supposed to go

00:19:45.160 --> 00:19:50.480
[Amit Varma]: on and on yeah no I'll ask you a lot more because yeah all this is so

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:53.680
[Amit Varma]: fascinating to me and I was I was actually you know I live in Andheri so I

00:19:53.680 --> 00:19:56.800
[Amit Varma]: was thinking yeah okay humble beginnings in Matunga but suddenly you said

00:19:56.800 --> 00:20:00.600
[Amit Varma]: Napiency Road and Napiency Road is so posh by the way for people who don't

00:20:00.600 --> 00:20:04.160
[Amit Varma]: know Bombay that I've never even been there in more than 20 years because I

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:09.000
[Amit Varma]: don't have posh friends it is super posh I was I was struck by you know I'm

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:12.720
[Amit Varma]: really glad that you spoke about your great-grandparents because one of the

00:20:12.720 --> 00:20:17.000
[Amit Varma]: things that sort of struck me and it's something that I was I've been kind of

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:20.720
[Amit Varma]: thinking about recently because I have to move house soon as soon as the

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:23.880
[Amit Varma]: lockdown gets over and the situation gets better and I'm just thinking of all

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:28.640
[Amit Varma]: the things we have to shift and how many of them seem to be you know needless

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:33.480
[Amit Varma]: just things that you accumulate over the sort of the decades and and you know the

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:37.880
[Amit Varma]: thousands of books even feel like extremely out of place because you know

00:20:37.880 --> 00:20:42.680
[Amit Varma]: I do most of my reading on the Kindle or on the laptop and all of that it's very

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:48.040
[Amit Varma]: striking and something that we may not think about or take for granted that the

00:20:48.040 --> 00:20:51.320
[Amit Varma]: things you mentioned that they used to shift with were you know you mentioned

00:20:51.320 --> 00:20:55.200
[Amit Varma]: cooking utensils first so you have your cooking utensils and then whatever

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:59.320
[Amit Varma]: clothes you have and that's pretty much it while today you know in our modern

00:20:59.320 --> 00:21:04.240
[Amit Varma]: worlds we love so much furniture so much electronics so many books so many curios

00:21:04.240 --> 00:21:08.680
[Amit Varma]: and artifacts and all of that and and yet at a time cooking utensils are so

00:21:08.680 --> 00:21:12.400
[Amit Varma]: fundamental like I remember I did an episode with Anshul Malhotra on

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:16.000
[Amit Varma]: partition where she's done this beautiful book on objects that people

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:19.880
[Amit Varma]: bring with them from partition and in many cases ever utensils because when

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:23.480
[Amit Varma]: people ran away from home that was the one thing they took with them partly for

00:21:23.480 --> 00:21:27.160
[Amit Varma]: practical reasons of course because you know you may have to cook your own food

00:21:27.160 --> 00:21:30.520
[Amit Varma]: while you're on the road and it's good to have something to cook it in because

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:35.160
[Amit Varma]: you know obviously you can't take some dal in your palm and hold that over the

00:21:35.160 --> 00:21:38.760
[Amit Varma]: fire but did food and cooking was it ever something that ever interested you

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:42.020
[Amit Varma]: did you have to learn to cook when you were a kid especially when you were in a

00:21:42.020 --> 00:21:46.240
[Amit Varma]: joint family with five mothers so to say three aunts one grandmom one mom was the

00:21:46.240 --> 00:21:51.080
[Amit Varma]: kitchen a different kind of space like today you know in our experience of say

00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:54.960
[Amit Varma]: nuclear households the kitchen isn't such a big deal but I can imagine that

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:58.960
[Amit Varma]: in a large joint family the kitchen would have played a different kind of

00:21:58.960 --> 00:22:04.240
[Amit Varma]: role where almost a community space as it were do you have memories of any of

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:08.480
[Amit Varma]: that or is food just something that you know you ate absentmindedly while

00:22:08.480 --> 00:22:13.720
[Guest]: growing up and didn't really think about yeah it's a very good question and you

00:22:13.720 --> 00:22:17.600
[Guest]: know I get asked this quite a bit because people want to know if I was

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:23.440
[Guest]: always into cooking and did I start early see because having so many women

00:22:23.440 --> 00:22:28.000
[Guest]: in the house and like I said I was the first child in my generation I was not

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.880
[Guest]: expected to enter the kitchen at all in fact if I even entered the kitchen I

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:36.760
[Guest]: would be shooed away saying go read go practice music or do something do

00:22:36.760 --> 00:22:40.600
[Guest]: something worthwhile don't waste your time in the kitchen that was what was

00:22:40.600 --> 00:22:44.640
[Guest]: told to me and despite the fact that like I said they were very traditional

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:49.280
[Guest]: and conservative but I think it's something about this being in a Bombay a

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:53.800
[Guest]: very aspirational city that there was the subtle thing that you had to do

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:57.680
[Guest]: something great in your life you know no matter what so you need to focus on

00:22:57.680 --> 00:23:02.800
[Guest]: building those skills and that though I never was overtly a pressure to do

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:07.320
[Guest]: anything like nobody ever scolded me if I didn't get first rank but I did have

00:23:07.320 --> 00:23:13.200
[Guest]: that pressure on myself since I was very young I don't know beat something like a

00:23:13.200 --> 00:23:17.920
[Guest]: competitive spirit or if I do something I want to excel at it I don't want to be

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:22.640
[Guest]: in the middle like if I put an effort I need to see some good results for that

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:29.000
[Guest]: so yeah so I never I hardly ever entered the kitchen and like even my

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:34.880
[Guest]: grandfather I even remember as late as you know in before 12th standard I was

00:23:34.880 --> 00:23:41.600
[Guest]: attending these classes in Dadar Agarwal classes to study maths and physics and

00:23:41.600 --> 00:23:46.760
[Guest]: stuff to you know get good marks in the 12th science exams and those days we

00:23:46.760 --> 00:23:51.160
[Guest]: were living in Mulund and I just take the local train leave home at around 5

00:23:51.160 --> 00:23:55.560
[Guest]: 30 a.m. so I could reach the class at 7 o'clock when it started in the morning

00:23:55.560 --> 00:24:01.720
[Guest]: and my grandfather would wake up at 5 and he would like standard two slices of

00:24:01.720 --> 00:24:06.240
[Guest]: bread with jam and butter a glass of milk or whatever it would be there for

00:24:06.240 --> 00:24:12.920
[Guest]: me ready when I got up at 5, gulp it down so 5.30 like get ready and 5.30 out

00:24:12.920 --> 00:24:16.360
[Guest]: of the house and he would take me to the bus stop and then I would take the train

00:24:16.360 --> 00:24:21.480
[Guest]: etc so there was nowhere expected that I had to do this on my own like even my

00:24:21.480 --> 00:24:25.680
[Guest]: grandfather would do these things for me their priorities were very clear you

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:31.000
[Guest]: have to study well and you have to do something good with your life and also

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:34.080
[Guest]: for them it was like a kitchen was like what are you going to do in the kitchen

00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:38.080
[Guest]: how is it going to help your life in any way and maybe later on when you're

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:40.960
[Guest]: independent anyway you'll have to be wasting your time here so might as well

00:24:40.960 --> 00:24:46.000
[Guest]: don't do it now when there are so many of us to handle and in my family also

00:24:46.000 --> 00:24:49.560
[Guest]: because they were so traditional they were very exacting requirements of how

00:24:49.560 --> 00:24:54.160
[Guest]: everything has to be made so there was no place for a person like me with no

00:24:54.160 --> 00:24:58.280
[Guest]: real knowledge about what exactly is going into anything and if I come they

00:24:58.280 --> 00:25:01.520
[Guest]: think I'm only going to mess up something so that was the other reason I

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:06.600
[Guest]: was not allowed and like they were so super careful every time they were

00:25:06.600 --> 00:25:11.120
[Guest]: making these like say Diwali sweets or some festival things they would keep the

00:25:11.120 --> 00:25:16.440
[Guest]: gas on the floor and my grandmother would sit on the floor and make all

00:25:16.440 --> 00:25:20.040
[Guest]: these things because it's it's tough to keep standing for like two and three

00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:24.920
[Guest]: hours and you know do it on the standing counter so when that used to happen when

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:28.840
[Guest]: I was a much younger child you literally draw like a Lakshman Rekha outside the

00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:32.080
[Guest]: kitchen and say you're not supposed to cross this and I would have all these

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:37.640
[Guest]: insane super aromas coming to me and I could not even cross the line and go

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:40.600
[Guest]: into the kitchen because they were worried that there's this whole plan of

00:25:40.600 --> 00:25:45.240
[Guest]: boiling oil and you know they wouldn't trust me to be safe around that so those

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:50.560
[Guest]: are the things that I remember and the other very fond memories like these

00:25:50.560 --> 00:25:55.800
[Guest]: Diwali times when my aunts even much later on my grandmother they would all

00:25:55.800 --> 00:26:00.480
[Guest]: sit on the floor you know that was like a very unique and a fun situation

00:26:00.480 --> 00:26:04.160
[Guest]: because usually that cooking was so mechanical and you know one person

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:07.240
[Guest]: standing on the counter and finishing off the things but this seemed like such

00:26:07.240 --> 00:26:10.960
[Guest]: a community fun exercise they'll be gossiping about something or the other

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:15.360
[Guest]: and I would feel like I'm missing out on all the fun because I'm not even

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:21.560
[Guest]: allowed to go inside so I grew up not knowing much about cooking at all and I

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:26.200
[Guest]: think when I was 10 or something I learned to make a dosa from my

00:26:26.200 --> 00:26:30.280
[Guest]: grandmother like standing on the stool and you know learning how it's made

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:34.800
[Guest]: that's because I kind of liked that process and it felt a bit like a craft

00:26:34.800 --> 00:26:40.480
[Guest]: fun kind of project to do so that's one thing I learned I knew to make tea and

00:26:40.480 --> 00:26:45.440
[Guest]: that's about it I knew nothing else growing up I just went to college with

00:26:45.440 --> 00:26:49.520
[Amit Varma]: only this much knowledge about cooking yeah and no one of the things that you

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:53.880
[Amit Varma]: that you said that struck me and I'm just thinking aloud here is that

00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:56.840
[Amit Varma]: perhaps you were given this push because you were in Bombay and it was this

00:26:56.840 --> 00:26:59.840
[Amit Varma]: feeling of that hey we are in Bombay it's an opportunity so don't let it go

00:26:59.840 --> 00:27:03.920
[Amit Varma]: to waste and you know which might not have been the case in a smaller town and

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:08.720
[Amit Varma]: I think as an extension of that I wonder if one could then say that a lot of

00:27:08.720 --> 00:27:12.160
[Amit Varma]: parents who themselves have come up the hard way who were to fight for

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:16.640
[Amit Varma]: everything who perhaps just because of the times but perhaps because they've

00:27:16.640 --> 00:27:20.520
[Amit Varma]: actually moved their way up that because they've had to fight all the way and and

00:27:20.520 --> 00:27:25.160
[Amit Varma]: now they can you know offer the kid more opportunities they pressurize the kid so

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:29.360
[Amit Varma]: much because they feel that it's now almost obligatory to make use of the

00:27:29.360 --> 00:27:34.280
[Amit Varma]: opportunities that they never had and I wonder if there's something similar at

00:27:34.280 --> 00:27:38.800
[Amit Varma]: play so tell me something in these years growing up as you were where you are

00:27:38.800 --> 00:27:41.840
[Amit Varma]: both you know in a traditional family where in a sense you're rooted but also

00:27:41.840 --> 00:27:44.320
[Amit Varma]: you're driven you're ambitious you're doing things you're going to Agarwal's

00:27:44.320 --> 00:27:47.720
[Amit Varma]: classes and all of that and you're a science kid and a good student neither

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:52.960
[Amit Varma]: of which I ever was so what what's your conception of yourself at this time like

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:56.640
[Amit Varma]: you did go on to become a medical doctor and we'll chat about that more but at

00:27:56.640 --> 00:28:00.160
[Amit Varma]: this point in time as you're growing up in your through your childhood and

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:03.560
[Amit Varma]: through your teens and as you're getting to college what's your conception of

00:28:03.560 --> 00:28:07.280
[Amit Varma]: yourself do you have fantasies about what you will do later on in life are

00:28:07.280 --> 00:28:11.520
[Amit Varma]: there anything you could call either ambitions or dreams or are you just kind

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:15.160
[Amit Varma]: of going with the flow and just trying to excel in whatever is immediately in

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:19.960
[Amit Varma]: front of you which could be the exams or Agarwal's classes or whatever this is

00:28:19.960 --> 00:28:24.840
[Guest]: such a question that it's really making me introspect I have never thought about

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:29.720
[Guest]: this myself to be honest and I knew coming as a guest on your podcast is

00:28:29.720 --> 00:28:33.520
[Guest]: going to make me think a lot about myself and discover some things which I

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:38.400
[Guest]: had not really given a thought to earlier you know when I was born I was

00:28:38.400 --> 00:28:42.640
[Guest]: born in that Napiency Road house like I told you our neighbors their eldest

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:48.160
[Guest]: daughter was a was an IAS officer and on the 11th day or 12th day they have this

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:53.080
[Guest]: cradle ceremony for the baby and in my house because I was the first kid there

00:28:53.080 --> 00:28:57.800
[Guest]: was no earlier cradles in the house to put me in so they borrowed this cradle

00:28:57.800 --> 00:29:01.360
[Guest]: from the next-door neighbor that belonged to the lady who was already

00:29:01.360 --> 00:29:05.880
[Guest]: grown up by then she was the IAS officer and already in those days so they were

00:29:05.880 --> 00:29:09.880
[Guest]: all saying she are going to become an IAS officer that was like something that

00:29:09.880 --> 00:29:15.160
[Guest]: was driven to me I didn't even know what was IAS officer but I clearly remember

00:29:15.160 --> 00:29:19.320
[Guest]: that term from very early on in childhood like maybe when I was 3 or 4

00:29:19.320 --> 00:29:23.520
[Guest]: I knew that there's something like this IAS officer and my folks want me to

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:29.480
[Guest]: become that so that was the earliest thing of anything related to a career

00:29:29.480 --> 00:29:34.800
[Guest]: that I ever you know even came across that that you may have this choice later

00:29:34.800 --> 00:29:40.320
[Guest]: on in life that what to do in life you know and I was in grade 3 and 4 in our

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:44.680
[Guest]: school in the report card I would always get this my budding scientist something

00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:49.560
[Guest]: like that teachers would write a comment and I think at that age these kind of

00:29:49.560 --> 00:29:54.800
[Guest]: words somehow see I'm right now I'm almost 45 and I still remember those

00:29:54.800 --> 00:29:59.280
[Guest]: words that were written in my report card so I think when teachers write

00:29:59.280 --> 00:30:03.320
[Guest]: something like that and especially if the teachers you like write a comment

00:30:03.320 --> 00:30:07.080
[Guest]: like that on your report card it's somewhere just plays on your mind and

00:30:07.080 --> 00:30:13.000
[Guest]: you feel wow I am capable of this and it gives you that push and and that sense

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:17.600
[Guest]: that that is possible you know so I think that also stayed on my mind that

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:21.840
[Guest]: I maybe I'm supposed to do science maybe that's good for me but at the same time

00:30:21.840 --> 00:30:27.400
[Guest]: I also loved writing early on as a kid like I had a lot of me time lot of

00:30:27.400 --> 00:30:30.960
[Guest]: boredom because I didn't have a sibling for the longest time and I stayed with

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:35.920
[Guest]: my grandparents and I didn't have too many friends so all my spare time was

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:41.900
[Guest]: like spent writing something must be quite silly but I used to write and like

00:30:41.900 --> 00:30:45.720
[Guest]: small poems and all I my mom has still preserved some diary sometime and

00:30:45.720 --> 00:30:49.080
[Guest]: embarrassing embarrassingly she shows it to me at times it please I don't want

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:55.360
[Guest]: to see it now so I would keep writing and you know my aunts and my mom would

00:30:55.360 --> 00:30:59.480
[Guest]: also say I'm good at this maybe you know it's something it's not not something I

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:04.000
[Guest]: ever thought about myself but there's a lot of little external influences that

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:08.360
[Guest]: unknowingly just settle down in the different you know levels of your head

00:31:08.360 --> 00:31:13.520
[Guest]: and you feel maybe this maybe that I definitely loved English I loved words

00:31:13.520 --> 00:31:18.840
[Guest]: and I loved the language and I said maybe this is this will make me happy

00:31:18.840 --> 00:31:23.080
[Guest]: but in those days also there was a thing that you know if you got the least marks

00:31:23.080 --> 00:31:27.680
[Guest]: in college is where you went to arts by default so the thing was you get a 95

00:31:27.680 --> 00:31:30.600
[Guest]: plus you have you don't even have to think you're going into science

00:31:30.600 --> 00:31:34.440
[Guest]: somewhere like 70s you're going to commerce and how 50s you're going to

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:39.360
[Guest]: arts and as stupid as that may sound today but that was how things were for

00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:45.540
[Guest]: 70s kids we didn't really have any other options and for girls oh you like a good

00:31:45.540 --> 00:31:50.280
[Guest]: you know feminine instinct and also medicine is good for you and boys you

00:31:50.280 --> 00:31:54.000
[Guest]: like straightaway engineering you were not expected to think so much there was

00:31:54.000 --> 00:31:57.680
[Guest]: nothing like career counseling and what is good for you what's your aptitude

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:02.040
[Guest]: nothing of that sort I think I was always going with the flow I never

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:07.720
[Guest]: really thought too much into it and neither did my family put like too much

00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:12.480
[Guest]: thought like what is she going to do and they just thought whatever she does she

00:32:12.480 --> 00:32:16.560
[Guest]: will do it okay like I was pretty self-motivated and driven so they didn't

00:32:16.560 --> 00:32:21.280
[Guest]: really bother about what I'm going to do in my life and neither did I think about

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:26.440
[Amit Varma]: it to be honest so you know I did an episode with Sharda Ugra recently and in

00:32:26.440 --> 00:32:29.880
[Amit Varma]: that Sharda was talking about how she was a 70s kid and I was saying I'm an

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:34.280
[Amit Varma]: 80s kid and the interesting thing is that you know you just gave your age

00:32:34.280 --> 00:32:37.400
[Amit Varma]: away and I've realized I'm a little older than you and yet you are

00:32:37.400 --> 00:32:40.720
[Amit Varma]: describing yourself as a 70s kid which I don't do because I don't really

00:32:40.720 --> 00:32:44.400
[Amit Varma]: remember I was I was I was too much of a kid in the 70s to remember any of it so

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:49.000
[Amit Varma]: I think of myself more as an 80s kid because that is where my memories of

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:53.200
[Amit Varma]: kiddery were but I'm struck by a phrase that you used here which is something

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:57.240
[Amit Varma]: that you know was not even a phrase back in the day because it was the default

00:32:57.240 --> 00:33:02.760
[Amit Varma]: and today is very much a phrase which is me time you know back in the day we had

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:07.000
[Amit Varma]: no me time because you know we have no laptops we have no internet we have no

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:10.200
[Amit Varma]: cell phones we have nothing you know if you're lucky we have some books around

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:14.760
[Amit Varma]: us but even even for a regular reader how much can you read so you you kind of

00:33:14.760 --> 00:33:20.080
[Amit Varma]: do get a lot of me time that way and I know exactly what that's like so tell me

00:33:20.080 --> 00:33:23.320
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about what kind of books did you read and what kind of writing

00:33:23.320 --> 00:33:27.840
[Amit Varma]: did you do like firstly everything we write as children is obviously cringeworthy

00:33:27.840 --> 00:33:30.880
[Amit Varma]: later if you're going to look at it with adult eyes obviously it's not going to

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:34.880
[Amit Varma]: pass standard no you should see what I wrote as a kid but nevertheless so what

00:33:34.880 --> 00:33:38.640
[Amit Varma]: what were the kind of books that you read in those days and what kind of

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:44.560
[Guest]: writing did you like to do you know I have memories of this book a bookshop in

00:33:44.560 --> 00:33:50.400
[Guest]: Napiency Road I think it was called Shobna I'm not very sure but I remember

00:33:50.400 --> 00:33:55.280
[Guest]: going there like every fortnight with my grandfather and I've just opened that

00:33:55.280 --> 00:34:00.880
[Guest]: door and this gush of cool very nice smelling air-conditioning would hit my

00:34:00.880 --> 00:34:06.200
[Guest]: face and that itself was like so welcoming and that was just like one of

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:10.760
[Guest]: the many pleasures to be had when you enter that store those were still my

00:34:10.760 --> 00:34:15.440
[Guest]: fairy tale and those kind of book reading days so I would pick up one book

00:34:15.440 --> 00:34:20.040
[Guest]: and it was it was a store not a library so whatever my grandfather bought within

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:22.940
[Guest]: 10 minutes of coming home I would have finished reading that and he said okay

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:27.720
[Guest]: now you either read the same book again and again until I take you back or you

00:34:27.720 --> 00:34:31.120
[Guest]: read something else so don't come and tell me it's finished so take your own

00:34:31.120 --> 00:34:37.120
[Guest]: time with it so I think that that really made me eager made me an eager reader

00:34:37.120 --> 00:34:41.960
[Guest]: just like taking me to the bookstore as a treat you know a lot of summer

00:34:41.960 --> 00:34:47.120
[Guest]: holidays and holidays because I was living with my grandparents I would be

00:34:47.120 --> 00:34:50.400
[Guest]: shooed off to my great-grandparents house during the holidays because I have

00:34:50.400 --> 00:34:54.560
[Guest]: to go somewhere right I can't stay in the same place forever and holiday time

00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:58.280
[Guest]: you have to shift and you know spend time with your other relatives or do

00:34:58.280 --> 00:35:02.280
[Guest]: something that's what we used to do in like we had nothing else fancy to do in

00:35:02.280 --> 00:35:07.240
[Guest]: our days my great-grandfather was a voracious reader like even like whatever

00:35:07.240 --> 00:35:13.060
[Guest]: newspaper that he used to read literally end to end every word and sometimes he

00:35:13.060 --> 00:35:17.640
[Guest]: would be lazing on in his easy chair and he would say that okay this full page

00:35:17.640 --> 00:35:21.200
[Guest]: you have to read to me now and I would keep watching like is he asleep can I

00:35:21.200 --> 00:35:25.160
[Guest]: stop reading because he doesn't seem to be listening to anything and sometimes

00:35:25.160 --> 00:35:30.600
[Guest]: it used to be about politics and like absolutely the kind of subjects that you

00:35:30.600 --> 00:35:34.300
[Guest]: may not be interested in at all or it makes no sense to you but he just wanted

00:35:34.300 --> 00:35:38.360
[Guest]: you to read it to know that there are all these different words and all this

00:35:38.360 --> 00:35:43.280
[Guest]: different vocabulary and sometimes he would make me like read something

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:47.760
[Guest]: complicated and say now write this very simply you know in one page or something

00:35:47.760 --> 00:35:54.760
[Guest]: so that that's the kind of vacation fun quote-unquote that we had and also the

00:35:54.760 --> 00:35:58.080
[Guest]: big thing that made me interested in these things that when I used to go

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:02.280
[Guest]: there during my holidays I was out of my comfort zone I didn't have my familiar

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:06.960
[Guest]: books and toys and whatever you know things that I was comfortable doing in

00:36:06.960 --> 00:36:11.360
[Guest]: my free time so I had to find out new things to do and they had this balcony

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:14.760
[Guest]: and in that King Circle apartment complex there were like four or five

00:36:14.760 --> 00:36:18.520
[Guest]: buildings and in between there was this big courtyard kind of space with a water

00:36:18.520 --> 00:36:24.240
[Guest]: tank and all that and every afternoon a bunch of cows would come and sit there

00:36:24.240 --> 00:36:29.240
[Guest]: for relaxation so these cows would be sitting there and swatting flies and

00:36:29.240 --> 00:36:34.360
[Guest]: generally like chilled out and you can't imagine I've like watched them for hours

00:36:34.360 --> 00:36:40.120
[Guest]: on end to kill my time because I had nothing better to do and other thing was

00:36:40.120 --> 00:36:43.440
[Guest]: all because that was like the open courtyard where all the other buildings

00:36:43.440 --> 00:36:47.400
[Guest]: could see what's happening all the vendors would come there right from salt

00:36:47.400 --> 00:36:52.640
[Guest]: guy to banana guy vegetable guy and my other favorite pastime was to mimic all

00:36:52.640 --> 00:36:58.720
[Guest]: their calls and because you know that this balcony level was like say to the

00:36:58.720 --> 00:37:03.560
[Guest]: level of my shoulder or something so I could I would just mimic the call back

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:07.000
[Guest]: and hide under that thing so they would like wonder where is the sound coming

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:10.880
[Guest]: from and at the lower level there were these Jali so I could see that he's

00:37:10.880 --> 00:37:15.800
[Guest]: wondering where's the sound coming from so these were the kind of creative

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:20.600
[Guest]: vacation pastimes that I had because I was no one else to play with and it's a

00:37:20.600 --> 00:37:24.040
[Guest]: new place and I had I used to always take too much time making any friends so

00:37:24.040 --> 00:37:28.000
[Guest]: it's not the place where I live regularly so I would not go out and play

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:32.400
[Guest]: with I don't know these people I can't go so this was you know all part of this

00:37:32.400 --> 00:37:38.320
[Guest]: creative process and a way in which boredom really spurs on your creativity

00:37:38.320 --> 00:37:42.400
[Guest]: to do something nice because you're so bored out of your skull and you say okay

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:46.960
[Guest]: let me do something fun you know let me write or let me draw something or let me

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:53.000
[Guest]: create something and later on I think I read the philosopher J Krishnamurti has

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:57.200
[Guest]: written something very similar that boredom is the best way to creativity

00:37:57.200 --> 00:38:04.080
[Guest]: and I was like well I knew this from my childhood itself so I mean I don't

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:08.840
[Guest]: really remember what books I specifically read but a lot of fairy

00:38:08.840 --> 00:38:14.880
[Guest]: tales Grimm's you know some inspirational autobiographies and and

00:38:14.880 --> 00:38:18.880
[Guest]: then later on of course when I became a teenager I read all the usual paperbacks

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:23.080
[Guest]: that Sidney Sheldon Daniel Steele everything that was available in India

00:38:23.080 --> 00:38:26.920
[Guest]: yeah I never read a Milson Boone though for the simple reason that I found that

00:38:26.920 --> 00:38:29.880
[Guest]: it's too small I'll finish it too quickly so I don't even want to get into

00:38:29.880 --> 00:38:36.640
[Guest]: this so I was reading the usual novels fiction I was not much into nonfiction I

00:38:36.640 --> 00:38:40.480
[Amit Varma]: would love medical fiction also excellent you know and you know speaking

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:43.600
[Amit Varma]: of boredom being a spur to creativity there's also the saying about an idle

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:47.760
[Amit Varma]: mind being a devil's workshop but that that courtyard sounds so fascinating it

00:38:47.760 --> 00:38:52.720
[Amit Varma]: sounds like a kind of a setting for an urban malgudi days as it were and indeed

00:38:52.720 --> 00:38:57.360
[Amit Varma]: you know courtyards do have a special place in some Indian literature as well

00:38:57.360 --> 00:39:02.800
[Amit Varma]: because almost like a gathering place of sorts and as the other sort of thread

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:06.320
[Amit Varma]: that I instantly connected with and I don't know if it's it's probably going

00:39:06.320 --> 00:39:11.680
[Amit Varma]: to be a shared memory only for people of our generation is when you brought books

00:39:11.680 --> 00:39:15.000
[Amit Varma]: and air-conditioning together you know you mentioned that you used to go to

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:18.620
[Amit Varma]: that store whatever it was in a PNC Road and the door would open and it blast of

00:39:18.620 --> 00:39:23.640
[Amit Varma]: AC and I remember when I was in college in Ferguson College Pune I used to spend

00:39:23.640 --> 00:39:27.600
[Amit Varma]: my afternoons at the British Council Library there on FC Road pretending to

00:39:27.600 --> 00:39:30.440
[Amit Varma]: read books but actually combining my love for books with my love for

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:35.600
[Amit Varma]: air-conditioning so stuff that you know perhaps a future generation may take for

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:39.000
[Amit Varma]: granted you know unless there is a solar flare or something and there is no

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:43.560
[Amit Varma]: electricity and then they'll suddenly say how what was that we just went when

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:47.520
[Amit Varma]: they realize the importance of the internet and the electricity but I'm

00:39:47.520 --> 00:39:51.560
[Amit Varma]: sounding too much like an old fogey now so tell me more about doing medical

00:39:51.560 --> 00:39:55.800
[Amit Varma]: because on the one hand in this and you know in previous interviews you've kind

00:39:55.800 --> 00:40:00.380
[Amit Varma]: of spoken about how you sort of wandered into doing medical because that was what

00:40:00.380 --> 00:40:03.400
[Amit Varma]: was expected from a good student who were getting the kind of marks that you

00:40:03.400 --> 00:40:07.920
[Amit Varma]: were but on the other hand you clearly had the aptitude and the bent of mind

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:12.360
[Amit Varma]: that a doctor actually needs and that bent of mind actually comes through in

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:16.720
[Amit Varma]: pretty much everything you have done since as well from what I can see which

00:40:16.720 --> 00:40:22.320
[Amit Varma]: is you know sort of organized systematic going deeper and deeper into sort of

00:40:22.320 --> 00:40:26.760
[Amit Varma]: first principles root causes all of that so tell me a little bit about what that

00:40:26.760 --> 00:40:30.680
[Amit Varma]: process of doing medical was like did you you know was it natural for you was

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:34.600
[Amit Varma]: it easy for you was it something that interested you and was it something that

00:40:34.600 --> 00:40:39.000
[Amit Varma]: you saw yourself doing for the rest of your life what was all of that like I

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:43.280
[Guest]: was always going with the flow and I had really not given a thought as to what

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:49.360
[Guest]: career I want to pursue and I got marks good enough to get a seat in a medical

00:40:49.360 --> 00:40:54.160
[Guest]: college in Bombay and maybe if it was not in Bombay and if it was some rural

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:57.960
[Guest]: area my family would have thought twice about sending me away from this very

00:40:57.960 --> 00:41:03.360
[Guest]: sheltered existence of the last 17 years but it was very much in Bombay and I

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:09.080
[Guest]: didn't have to stay in a hostel and things like that so I took admission in

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:13.800
[Guest]: that but I really didn't know what that life would be like even how would it be

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:18.160
[Guest]: to study medicine how would it be to practice medicine one thing I definitely

00:41:18.160 --> 00:41:21.840
[Guest]: knew that it required a lot of dedication commitment and sacrifice to

00:41:21.840 --> 00:41:26.160
[Guest]: practice medicine unless you are in a very specific branch like say pathology

00:41:26.160 --> 00:41:29.840
[Guest]: but you could still get away with fixed working hours but if you were to

00:41:29.840 --> 00:41:33.880
[Guest]: practice medicine or surgery then definitely you had to be available all

00:41:33.880 --> 00:41:39.240
[Guest]: the time and when I joined I said you know yeah I if I do this I'm going to do

00:41:39.240 --> 00:41:43.560
[Guest]: it well I am going to dedicate my life to being a good doctor if I get into

00:41:43.560 --> 00:41:47.440
[Guest]: medical college it's not just you know studying for the heck of it because now

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:51.600
[Guest]: that I have got a seat I'm going to make the best of it you know there's this

00:41:51.600 --> 00:41:56.480
[Guest]: incident that happened when I joined medical college it was the year of the

00:41:56.480 --> 00:42:03.520
[Guest]: Mandal Commission and the admissions had got very delayed so you know in my times

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:07.760
[Guest]: the first year MBBS second MBBS and third MBBS were one and a half one and

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:10.960
[Guest]: a half one and a half years each so a total of four and a half years of

00:42:10.960 --> 00:42:14.120
[Guest]: studies and one year of internship so that was five and a half years to

00:42:14.120 --> 00:42:18.680
[Guest]: graduate so now in this one and a half years we had already joined six months

00:42:18.680 --> 00:42:23.120
[Guest]: late because of the delay in the admission process when people are still

00:42:23.120 --> 00:42:28.320
[Guest]: figuring out what kind of admissions to happen etc so but the first MBBS is also

00:42:28.320 --> 00:42:33.400
[Guest]: a huge learning like within the first year itself your vocabulary goes up by

00:42:33.400 --> 00:42:37.840
[Guest]: some 10,000 words because you are learning the kind of language which we

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:44.440
[Guest]: don't use as laypeople and just that kind of adjustment to seeing certain

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:49.040
[Guest]: things in such a stark light which was like a sheltered existence like me I've

00:42:49.040 --> 00:42:55.800
[Guest]: never been exposed to anything and day one of medical college there is maybe a

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:58.720
[Guest]: little bit of some orientation or something huh you'll have these many

00:42:58.720 --> 00:43:01.960
[Guest]: classes you'll have to get this much percentage this is the past percentage

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:07.720
[Guest]: some very basic orientation and then you know you're told come to the Anatomy

00:43:07.720 --> 00:43:13.880
[Guest]: Hall so now they're 50 girls and 50 boys hundred kids in a class and a good like

00:43:13.880 --> 00:43:19.160
[Guest]: 50-50 gender distribution there and okay you just wander into the Anatomy Hall

00:43:19.160 --> 00:43:25.520
[Guest]: and first you're hit by that smell of formalin which literally makes you tear

00:43:25.520 --> 00:43:30.360
[Guest]: up and like where am I come is someone like you know throwing gas some kind of

00:43:30.360 --> 00:43:34.560
[Guest]: poisonous gas on my face by the time you recover from that you realize there are

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:38.720
[Guest]: tables and tables of naked dead bodies that you're staring at because it's a

00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:44.640
[Guest]: dissection hall so all the unclaimed corpses are there and here you are with

00:43:44.640 --> 00:43:49.640
[Guest]: a bunch of boys and girls that you've never met before in your life and you're

00:43:49.640 --> 00:43:55.720
[Guest]: facing this scene which is like it's like a shock like I cannot explain I

00:43:55.720 --> 00:44:00.080
[Guest]: don't think I've been so shocked in my life ever maybe today's kids may not

00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:04.480
[Guest]: feel that way but we were still very innocent growing up and we didn't have

00:44:04.480 --> 00:44:09.560
[Guest]: any exposure to any such gory stuff on TV or you know like Netflix that kids

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:14.200
[Guest]: now they just see and they brush off but for someone like me and I could

00:44:14.200 --> 00:44:17.520
[Guest]: definitely tell it was the same for the boys and the girls in my class and it

00:44:17.520 --> 00:44:22.440
[Guest]: was like a big big shock so that was like day one you feel like where have I

00:44:22.440 --> 00:44:30.160
[Guest]: come you know and so that that smell and the sight and that general embarrassment

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:35.600
[Guest]: and everything put together so that was like and there were other classes like

00:44:35.600 --> 00:44:40.280
[Guest]: in biochemistry and physiology but this is the one that stuck to me and I will

00:44:40.280 --> 00:44:46.160
[Guest]: never forget that experience of that first day but we also adapt to something

00:44:46.160 --> 00:44:52.880
[Guest]: strange like this so quickly. The new normal as it were. Exactly that new normal and within

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:59.160
[Guest]: like a couple of months we got used to seeing our anatomy professors

00:44:59.160 --> 00:45:03.240
[Guest]: they will open their box on that very dissection table and start

00:45:03.240 --> 00:45:07.480
[Guest]: eating their lunch and we would not cringe to see that also like you know

00:45:07.480 --> 00:45:13.360
[Guest]: there's this dead body cut open in different stages and you know cadaver to

00:45:13.360 --> 00:45:17.520
[Guest]: call it by the scientific term and somebody's just eating their lunch very

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:21.600
[Amit Varma]: coolly and like sharing do you want to eat this and that's also not advisable

00:45:21.600 --> 00:45:26.920
[Guest]: right because it's not to be honest but I mean maybe I'm exaggerating a little

00:45:26.920 --> 00:45:30.960
[Guest]: bit but even holding it in your hand with this view but it's not very

00:45:30.960 --> 00:45:35.160
[Guest]: different from us watching absolutely gory stuff on Netflix and you know

00:45:35.160 --> 00:45:40.240
[Guest]: eating our food in today's times we still do that right so but that that

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:46.880
[Guest]: also we got used to that and I think the other very very good memory of this

00:45:46.880 --> 00:45:50.800
[Guest]: whole anatomy thing that I was still getting used to that it was my birthday

00:45:50.800 --> 00:45:57.120
[Guest]: and you know we spent three three months dissecting each like one is HFN which is

00:45:57.120 --> 00:46:02.080
[Guest]: head face and neck then what we call supex the arms then chest and abdomen

00:46:02.080 --> 00:46:06.800
[Guest]: and then the lower extremities so in the head face and neck one very important

00:46:06.800 --> 00:46:13.080
[Guest]: component is the brain where with a with a bone cutting machine the skull is cut

00:46:13.080 --> 00:46:17.920
[Guest]: open and then they remove the brain and we are you know we understand what is in

00:46:17.920 --> 00:46:24.440
[Guest]: the transverse section of each of the levels on the human brain right so it

00:46:24.440 --> 00:46:28.560
[Guest]: was my birthday and we were cutting the brain and everybody sang happy birthday

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:34.840
[Guest]: to me it was I think about it now it was very amusing then but I think about it

00:46:34.840 --> 00:46:39.200
[Guest]: now I think are we crazy or what like you know but but I think that's the

00:46:39.200 --> 00:46:43.800
[Guest]: beauty of medical school you learn to see fun and you because your general

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:51.520
[Guest]: life is so you know full of fat books so much to study so much to learn you're

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:56.720
[Guest]: seeing disease you're seeing people in the worst stages of their life but you

00:46:56.720 --> 00:47:02.120
[Guest]: learn to see some humor in things like these which keep you going I think it

00:47:02.120 --> 00:47:08.120
[Guest]: provided some kind of you know soothing moments for the you're constantly

00:47:08.120 --> 00:47:13.520
[Guest]: under stress and as a kid who was into every possible non-sporting

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:19.080
[Guest]: extracurricular activity like music or drawing or drama or anything I had to

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:22.720
[Guest]: give up everything when I joined medicine so that was also very here I

00:47:22.720 --> 00:47:26.280
[Guest]: mean I had given up in 12th standard itself because had to make the most of

00:47:26.280 --> 00:47:32.040
[Guest]: time and study etc so that also felt very I can't say depressing but it felt

00:47:32.040 --> 00:47:35.760
[Guest]: like I had lost some of the fun in my life because these were the things I

00:47:35.760 --> 00:47:41.360
[Guest]: really enjoyed doing and so that's how we learn to make the most of these

00:47:41.360 --> 00:47:47.200
[Guest]: moments even in medical college when things felt like you know gloomy and you

00:47:47.200 --> 00:47:51.760
[Guest]: were it was a tough I remember that time and I remember that it did feel quite

00:47:51.760 --> 00:47:57.760
[Guest]: stressful because it was a huge jump getting used to regular science-based

00:47:57.760 --> 00:48:02.400
[Guest]: college where you just learned physics chemistry biology to learning about humans

00:48:02.400 --> 00:48:07.920
[Guest]: disease checking patients and you know hearing their stories and after all

00:48:07.920 --> 00:48:12.720
[Guest]: imagine we just 17 years old just kids right I think in India we start this so

00:48:12.720 --> 00:48:16.240
[Guest]: early in our foreign countries you have to finish your some full graduation and

00:48:16.240 --> 00:48:21.880
[Guest]: then start studying medicine so here you can if you pass all your years in one

00:48:21.880 --> 00:48:28.040
[Guest]: short you can well become a medical graduate at 22 which is very young to

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:33.760
[Guest]: kind of grasp the seriousness the realities and the kind of things that

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:38.440
[Guest]: accompany this very serious kind of study so these are my memories and yeah

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:43.240
[Guest]: I did well like I said the initial part of getting used to these things was a

00:48:43.240 --> 00:48:47.840
[Guest]: struggle until then I could somehow my school and college I could get through

00:48:47.840 --> 00:48:52.000
[Guest]: without studying much I would just you know pay attention in class and I could

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:56.640
[Guest]: manage to get good marks in the exams but this one some real effort had to go

00:48:56.640 --> 00:49:02.840
[Guest]: into reading so much the books were so so huge so heavy that you wouldn't even

00:49:02.840 --> 00:49:06.120
[Guest]: carry them anywhere you had to go where the book was the book couldn't come you

00:49:06.120 --> 00:49:10.800
[Guest]: couldn't carry the book to you but it did instill in me a certain kind of

00:49:10.800 --> 00:49:16.680
[Guest]: discipline of you know I used to wake up at 3 a.m. I think that's when I started

00:49:16.680 --> 00:49:20.560
[Guest]: becoming a morning person so if I had to leave for college at around 7 I would

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:25.760
[Guest]: study from 3 to 6 because again a college was a train ride away and you

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:29.440
[Guest]: were exhausted when you came back home you couldn't really focus on studying at

00:49:29.440 --> 00:49:33.680
[Guest]: that point of time so morning is when I felt this is the only time I can put in

00:49:33.680 --> 00:49:40.480
[Guest]: some some time to study I had a natural liking for surgery because since

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:45.300
[Guest]: childhood I love to do things create things and not just speculate about okay

00:49:45.300 --> 00:49:49.320
[Guest]: maybe will this work will that work so just get into the middle of the problem

00:49:49.320 --> 00:49:53.440
[Guest]: and solve it and I always thought that I will pursue surgery in some form or the

00:49:53.440 --> 00:49:59.420
[Guest]: other and I really liked it like think of it as a like a stitching or something

00:49:59.420 --> 00:50:03.280
[Guest]: but in a very complex scenario where someone's life depends on it right I

00:50:03.280 --> 00:50:08.080
[Guest]: loved surgery but I also liked medicine for the logic of it like a lot of things

00:50:08.080 --> 00:50:13.000
[Guest]: in medicine are very logical if you understand certain basic principles even

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:18.160
[Guest]: without knowing pathophysiology of a particular disease you can kind of

00:50:18.160 --> 00:50:21.320
[Guest]: interpret that this is how the things will progress and that kind of

00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:26.800
[Guest]: application of logic I love that in medicine absolutely hated Gainac I would

00:50:26.800 --> 00:50:32.240
[Guest]: like try to bunk every possible lecture without getting into trouble and just

00:50:32.240 --> 00:50:38.240
[Guest]: watching women screaming and that kind of thing was not my cup of tea at all so

00:50:38.240 --> 00:50:43.320
[Guest]: my first choice was surgery and my second choice was medicine but again I

00:50:43.320 --> 00:50:47.720
[Guest]: had not finalized anything in my head I said I'll see how it goes and take it as

00:50:47.720 --> 00:50:53.280
[Guest]: it comes and in my final year MBBS I got the results and I was declared failed

00:50:53.280 --> 00:50:57.880
[Guest]: and for someone who has been a topper all my life it's good that I'm

00:50:57.880 --> 00:51:01.400
[Guest]: reasonably strong mentally otherwise I don't know what would have been my

00:51:01.400 --> 00:51:05.920
[Guest]: reaction to that I just I just couldn't believe that something like this could

00:51:05.920 --> 00:51:10.480
[Guest]: happen and of course immediately I sent my papers for revaluation I had been

00:51:10.480 --> 00:51:16.080
[Guest]: declared fail in medicine now out of 1,500 marks in final MBBS 500 is

00:51:16.080 --> 00:51:18.920
[Guest]: medicine that's like one third of the entire curriculum which I have to

00:51:18.920 --> 00:51:24.440
[Guest]: restudy if I'm not declared passed in the reval and just the thought of going

00:51:24.440 --> 00:51:29.600
[Guest]: back to those books was like terrifying I just I said I had already done a good

00:51:29.600 --> 00:51:33.560
[Guest]: job studying in the first place why am I supposed to do this all over again and

00:51:33.560 --> 00:51:38.360
[Guest]: you know this was Bombay University and the center for all these corrections and

00:51:38.360 --> 00:51:42.240
[Guest]: these admin work was in Kalina so literally every three four days I would

00:51:42.240 --> 00:51:45.280
[Guest]: land up there and I would sit on that guy's head and think where is my paper

00:51:45.280 --> 00:51:50.200
[Guest]: where's my reval I've not got it the next exam is nearing the re-examination

00:51:50.200 --> 00:51:55.120
[Guest]: right and kind of I developed a rapport with that guy and he also started

00:51:55.120 --> 00:52:00.280
[Guest]: sympathizing saying this girl you know she's confident that she's going to pass

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:04.600
[Guest]: but the corrected paper is just not coming I kind of started losing hope and

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:09.120
[Guest]: I there was no other way but I started studying again for the next examination

00:52:09.120 --> 00:52:15.720
[Guest]: and just two days before the re-exam this guy calls me because by then I we

00:52:15.720 --> 00:52:20.360
[Guest]: were already exchanged phone numbers the admin guy in the university he calls me

00:52:20.360 --> 00:52:25.000
[Guest]: saying look your result has come you are passed so you come immediately and

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:28.600
[Guest]: collect the result I don't want to put it in post because then it will not

00:52:28.600 --> 00:52:34.080
[Guest]: reach you by the time you have to go for the next exam I think I went like I was

00:52:34.080 --> 00:52:39.000
[Guest]: in tears and happiness and like it was such a relief not to have to give that

00:52:39.000 --> 00:52:45.120
[Guest]: exam all over again and it was quite anti-climatic how my four and a half

00:52:45.120 --> 00:52:49.560
[Guest]: years of medical studies ended in this kind of very low and then a high kind of

00:52:49.560 --> 00:52:54.960
[Guest]: a situation and it was very excruciating and like I said we're not that old and

00:52:54.960 --> 00:53:00.480
[Guest]: we don't know how to take this kind of you know experiences in our life you're

00:53:00.480 --> 00:53:05.160
[Guest]: not used to it and it was quite traumatic and I even remember that today

00:53:05.160 --> 00:53:08.960
[Guest]: I wake up like with nightmares that I'm having to give my medical exam again

00:53:08.960 --> 00:53:15.960
[Guest]: medicine exam again so that's where my medicine journey ended and like all my

00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:19.920
[Guest]: classmates were shocked nobody could believe that I had failed and it was

00:53:19.920 --> 00:53:24.280
[Guest]: kind of very embarrassing for me like how am I even going to face these people

00:53:24.280 --> 00:53:28.520
[Guest]: you know not that I would think they would judge me but I was just judging

00:53:28.520 --> 00:53:35.560
[Guest]: myself so badly and yeah so that that stint ended there. It's interesting you

00:53:35.560 --> 00:53:39.960
[Amit Varma]: should talk about nightmares because you know I did arts and I did a BA in

00:53:39.960 --> 00:53:42.880
[Amit Varma]: English literature only reason I chose that was because I knew I wouldn't have

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:46.000
[Amit Varma]: to study and obviously I sailed through and I never really cared about exams at

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:51.400
[Amit Varma]: all and yet for years afterwards I would get a nightmare that I hadn't managed to

00:53:51.400 --> 00:53:54.640
[Amit Varma]: graduate or I wasn't getting my certificate or I had failed an exam

00:53:54.640 --> 00:53:58.760
[Amit Varma]: while during those years it was never even on my mind I didn't give a shit I

00:53:58.760 --> 00:54:02.880
[Amit Varma]: would have been happy to drop out so it's a very bizarre kind of not even a

00:54:02.880 --> 00:54:07.080
[Amit Varma]: nightmare like a persistent dream that thankfully stopped a few years ago I was

00:54:07.080 --> 00:54:10.720
[Amit Varma]: also stuck by how you said I became a morning person because I had to wake up

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:15.320
[Amit Varma]: at 3 a.m. like before this you were waking up as late as 5 a.m. having toast

00:54:15.320 --> 00:54:19.000
[Amit Varma]: and jam and going to your agarwal classes and you become a morning person

00:54:19.000 --> 00:54:24.120
[Amit Varma]: when you have to start waking up at 3. At an unearthly hour of 3. I love these

00:54:24.120 --> 00:54:28.040
[Amit Varma]: definitions but the part that I love best about what you just told me about

00:54:28.040 --> 00:54:32.080
[Amit Varma]: your medical years was that surreal scene that you cut open someone's skull

00:54:32.080 --> 00:54:35.080
[Amit Varma]: and then they sing happy birthday you know that that sounds like a Louis

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Bonheur film almost or I can imagine you know an Eli Roth film starting like that

00:54:40.240 --> 00:54:44.720
[Amit Varma]: where you have your opening scene close-up of skull the scalpel slices

00:54:44.720 --> 00:54:50.040
[Amit Varma]: through it it opens out you know brains oozing out and then happy birthday to

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:53.720
[Amit Varma]: you starts and that's when the title starts have you have you seen do you

00:54:53.720 --> 00:54:58.480
[Amit Varma]: watch horror films? Do I watch horror? No not much. There's this lovely series I

00:54:58.480 --> 00:55:04.000
[Amit Varma]: love by Eli Roth who some would know for also being an actor he acted in

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:08.680
[Amit Varma]: Tarantino's Inglourious Basterds as well but he directed the series of films

00:55:08.680 --> 00:55:15.560
[Amit Varma]: called Hostel which I think are absolutely brilliant there's just so much more so in

00:55:15.560 --> 00:55:22.760
[Amit Varma]: in Hostel 2 there's a lovely scene towards the end where I don't know if

00:55:22.760 --> 00:55:25.560
[Amit Varma]: I'll be judged for saying it's a lovely scene but it's a very striking scene

00:55:25.560 --> 00:55:28.960
[Amit Varma]: right at the end where the end credits are happening where a bunch of people

00:55:28.960 --> 00:55:33.760
[Amit Varma]: are kind of in the forest and two girls are being chased by someone I think and

00:55:33.760 --> 00:55:37.920
[Amit Varma]: one of the girls is caught and she is beheaded and then they play football

00:55:37.920 --> 00:55:42.520
[Amit Varma]: with a head and and and the end credits come on while they are playing football

00:55:42.520 --> 00:55:46.080
[Amit Varma]: with a head and I thought as such a striking kind of scene and that's

00:55:46.080 --> 00:55:52.760
[Amit Varma]: somehow what I remember. Mine was not as bad as that okay. It wasn't but it's the sort of the

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:57.680
[Amit Varma]: casualness of you know just that these are just body parts and what is a big

00:55:57.680 --> 00:56:01.160
[Amit Varma]: deal and the whole casualness of it there of course the body part became a

00:56:01.160 --> 00:56:04.680
[Amit Varma]: body part and not a living person because of actions on the part of the

00:56:04.680 --> 00:56:08.760
[Guest]: protagonist well I'm sure you and your class never killed anyone. I don't want

00:56:08.760 --> 00:56:13.760
[Guest]: people to judge me in thinking that you know we were too callous with the

00:56:13.760 --> 00:56:17.960
[Guest]: cadavers we we would always thought you know like be very respectful and

00:56:17.960 --> 00:56:22.920
[Guest]: grateful that people for whatever reason have landed up there and they are the

00:56:22.920 --> 00:56:27.760
[Guest]: very reason that we are able to learn about the human body and understand you

00:56:27.760 --> 00:56:31.920
[Guest]: know things which otherwise I mean at least in today's times of multimedia and

00:56:31.920 --> 00:56:36.000
[Guest]: stuff you can still get a fair understanding even if you didn't dissect

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:42.000
[Guest]: a single cadaver but it was like really so important and the absolute basis of

00:56:42.000 --> 00:56:46.640
[Guest]: everything you go on to learn later on in your medical school. And especially if

00:56:46.640 --> 00:56:52.000
[Amit Varma]: you want to be a surgeon it's kind of essential I guess. Yeah no I mean I was

00:56:52.000 --> 00:56:55.360
[Amit Varma]: drawn to that anecdote just by the element of black humor in there I guess

00:56:55.360 --> 00:57:01.000
[Amit Varma]: which is but let's let's move past that to something less black which is riots

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:06.240
[Amit Varma]: you know you've also described how a sort of a jarring incident in your early

00:57:06.240 --> 00:57:11.240
[Amit Varma]: years as a doctor which you remember as an important moment for your choosing to

00:57:11.240 --> 00:57:14.760
[Amit Varma]: give it up even though it had nothing to do with the profession per se tell me a

00:57:14.760 --> 00:57:19.760
[Guest]: little bit about that what went on there. Once I finished my medicine I was put

00:57:19.760 --> 00:57:26.300
[Guest]: into the internship rounds right so you have one year of internship and all my

00:57:26.300 --> 00:57:29.920
[Guest]: classmates and my good friends from college they had already started their

00:57:29.920 --> 00:57:33.280
[Guest]: internship five months before me because I was literally waiting for five months

00:57:33.280 --> 00:57:37.640
[Guest]: to even get my results and usually you do internships in groups like you know

00:57:37.640 --> 00:57:41.360
[Guest]: five six of you are together so you have like and this is the time you're

00:57:41.360 --> 00:57:46.400
[Guest]: actually starting to see patients as a doctor and although I must make this

00:57:46.400 --> 00:57:49.960
[Guest]: remark that most of the male patients would call us sister thinking that

00:57:49.960 --> 00:57:55.560
[Guest]: because we are women we can't be doctors and even like the guy who's the is the

00:57:55.560 --> 00:57:59.120
[Guest]: last ranker in our class is a doctor doctor he'll be like treating him with

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:04.200
[Guest]: so much respect but we are like nothing so we would go about in a group you know

00:58:04.200 --> 00:58:10.040
[Guest]: for internship and here I was left all by myself I had nobody like it's also so

00:58:10.040 --> 00:58:13.640
[Guest]: difficult that even it's the first time you're actually starting to do things on

00:58:13.640 --> 00:58:18.280
[Guest]: your own it's always good to have your back covered by your friends and you can

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:23.040
[Guest]: jointly discuss and say what's what are we going to do and you know even you're

00:58:23.040 --> 00:58:27.520
[Guest]: not questioned also on your own like if a senior professor is questioning is

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:30.640
[Guest]: questioning a group here it's like literally everywhere you're on your own

00:58:30.640 --> 00:58:36.120
[Guest]: and I felt very exposed and very lonely in the whole process of internship and

00:58:36.120 --> 00:58:40.760
[Guest]: again it was a huge transition from being a student to being a doctor and

00:58:40.760 --> 00:58:48.000
[Guest]: having no support no friends and being on on my own those days was very

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:53.040
[Guest]: difficult more than anything else for this reason I felt very bad that my

00:58:53.040 --> 00:58:57.920
[Guest]: papers weren't corrected properly because again it took made me rethink my

00:58:57.920 --> 00:59:03.200
[Guest]: decision and I thought maybe this is not the right thing for me just having been

00:59:03.200 --> 00:59:08.240
[Guest]: left alone and somehow I managed to still complete everything and I came out

00:59:08.240 --> 00:59:13.120
[Guest]: of my internship with a degree you know also there's this team of when a whole

00:59:13.120 --> 00:59:16.120
[Guest]: bunch of kids are doing this together to discuss okay we're going to apply

00:59:16.120 --> 00:59:19.120
[Guest]: they're going to give these exams we're going to study for it together we're

00:59:19.120 --> 00:59:22.420
[Guest]: going to apply to these colleges these are the specialties we want I was

00:59:22.420 --> 00:59:26.640
[Guest]: completely out of the loop in all those discussions and I had nobody to discuss

00:59:26.640 --> 00:59:32.000
[Guest]: those things with and even that kind of you know removed some of the steam from

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:36.960
[Guest]: my being very serious about pursuing a good career in surgery or something like

00:59:36.960 --> 00:59:41.440
[Guest]: that when I got my degree I said okay let me do one thing I will work as an

00:59:41.440 --> 00:59:47.240
[Guest]: RMO for some time which is like a medical officer and then I see you know

00:59:47.240 --> 00:59:52.240
[Guest]: depending on what I feel I will decide what I want to do further because now

00:59:52.240 --> 00:59:56.800
[Guest]: anyway I'm not in the rat race I have already fallen behind by six months so

00:59:56.800 --> 01:00:00.480
[Guest]: it doesn't matter there's no such rule that you have to join your PG as soon as

01:00:00.480 --> 01:00:04.680
[Guest]: you finish your graduation so I was working there and I was straight put

01:00:04.680 --> 01:00:09.000
[Guest]: into the ICU again very stressful because although I'm not expected to

01:00:09.000 --> 01:00:12.480
[Guest]: take any decisions or do things on my own there's always the guidance of the

01:00:12.480 --> 01:00:17.720
[Guest]: senior doctors the nurses etc but still it was like being thrown from straight

01:00:17.720 --> 01:00:21.340
[Guest]: from one thing into like a boiling hot pan and have to figure out what to do

01:00:21.340 --> 01:00:26.400
[Guest]: and you're only seeing critical patients again very stressful so that also made

01:00:26.400 --> 01:00:31.040
[Guest]: me rethink whether this kind of stresses for a person like me is it good for my

01:00:31.040 --> 01:00:36.960
[Guest]: temperament etc and I was there for like almost a year I think and somehow I was

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:41.080
[Guest]: learning all the you know ICU things around me because this is not something

01:00:41.080 --> 01:00:44.740
[Guest]: that you're trained in in your medical colleges ICU work is like a whole

01:00:44.740 --> 01:00:48.840
[Guest]: different ballgame everything is you know life and death decision kind of

01:00:48.840 --> 01:00:52.640
[Guest]: thing it's a very high stress thing and now the intensivists are the one who are

01:00:52.640 --> 01:00:57.600
[Guest]: like the forefront of the COVID warrior they are the ones taking these

01:00:57.600 --> 01:01:02.280
[Guest]: decisions although you know given the lack of that many number of intensives

01:01:02.280 --> 01:01:05.280
[Guest]: literally everybody has promoted themselves to be an intensivist because

01:01:05.280 --> 01:01:10.520
[Guest]: we have to save these lives I was getting used to that and then one very

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:17.200
[Guest]: high-profile politician got admitted after an accident and he had a emergency

01:01:17.200 --> 01:01:22.520
[Guest]: surgery and all that and you know somehow see any any such major accident

01:01:22.520 --> 01:01:27.200
[Guest]: and surgery this bound to be a risk of developing some complication or the

01:01:27.200 --> 01:01:31.040
[Guest]: other and which was clearly explained even before the surgery was done which

01:01:31.040 --> 01:01:33.840
[Guest]: is why most hospitals won't take such patients because they don't want the

01:01:33.840 --> 01:01:37.760
[Guest]: risk of someone dying on you when it was really not your fault to begin with

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:41.040
[Guest]: right fortunately once this person was discharged from the surgery he died

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:45.880
[Guest]: there was the crowd of at least 10 to 12 thousand people who are gathered

01:01:45.880 --> 01:01:51.280
[Guest]: outside the hospital we were some of us RMOs on duty some two three senior

01:01:51.280 --> 01:01:55.840
[Guest]: doctors some two three nurses all in the ICU and they locked up the ICU from

01:01:55.840 --> 01:02:03.280
[Guest]: outside after they took away the body and you know they set fire to the

01:02:03.280 --> 01:02:08.880
[Guest]: hospital and what it is they all just from what I know I didn't see this

01:02:08.880 --> 01:02:13.440
[Guest]: personally but I was told that they just lay down in front of the gate so neither

01:02:13.440 --> 01:02:18.960
[Guest]: firefighting you know fire engine nothing could even come in and they kind

01:02:18.960 --> 01:02:23.560
[Guest]: of sealed us from outside and here and because of the fire to avoid short

01:02:23.560 --> 01:02:27.400
[Guest]: circuit the powers were switched off and here you have patients on ventilators

01:02:27.400 --> 01:02:34.000
[Guest]: and other like it's I think it was a 20 or 25 or 30 bed ICU and you're worried

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:38.720
[Guest]: about how are these other patients going to survive without electricity and the

01:02:38.720 --> 01:02:43.520
[Guest]: burden of that of just losing people you're in the dark and those days of we

01:02:43.520 --> 01:02:47.880
[Guest]: had Nokia cell phone I think literally my battery was also out I could not call

01:02:47.880 --> 01:02:52.600
[Guest]: anyone and we were just hiding and we were inside and we were just praying and

01:02:52.600 --> 01:02:56.880
[Guest]: like somehow the patient's relatives started just lifting them and carrying

01:02:56.880 --> 01:03:00.760
[Guest]: them outside the hospital with all those IV lines and everything hanging and

01:03:00.760 --> 01:03:04.680
[Guest]: those kind of pictures were in the newspapers for a few weeks after that

01:03:04.680 --> 01:03:09.280
[Guest]: was very traumatizing and we were holed up in the ICU with the hospital burning

01:03:09.280 --> 01:03:15.160
[Guest]: outside and like the whole night and then the next morning and I think I had

01:03:15.160 --> 01:03:19.040
[Guest]: driven to the hospital I would rarely take the car but it was a Sunday or

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:22.740
[Guest]: something I said okay I'm not going to change to autos and buses and all and go

01:03:22.740 --> 01:03:26.600
[Guest]: and I took the car and the car got not just my car all the cars standing in the

01:03:26.600 --> 01:03:31.160
[Guest]: parking lot were completely charred we just came out to see their skeletons and

01:03:31.160 --> 01:03:36.200
[Guest]: this whole mental trauma the police dropped us home to each of our houses

01:03:36.200 --> 01:03:40.160
[Guest]: then we were asked to come and give statements and all that now we see so

01:03:40.160 --> 01:03:44.160
[Guest]: much you know we hear so much about violence against doctors and this mob

01:03:44.160 --> 01:03:49.400
[Guest]: mentality people beating up doctors etc but again those days I was new into this

01:03:49.400 --> 01:03:54.040
[Guest]: I'd never heard of something like this could happen I'm generally a very soft

01:03:54.040 --> 01:04:00.160
[Guest]: person don't like to get into any kind of you know controversy or just I like

01:04:00.160 --> 01:04:05.520
[Guest]: to mind my own business so this was was very very very traumatizing and I could

01:04:05.520 --> 01:04:08.320
[Guest]: just like I could not even go back to the hospital building where they had

01:04:08.320 --> 01:04:11.640
[Guest]: called us to give our you know statements and stuff even that was

01:04:11.640 --> 01:04:17.080
[Guest]: making me extremely panicky and I said I'm going to take a break from this

01:04:17.080 --> 01:04:23.400
[Guest]: hospital work because this has I think it was like a huge turning point and one

01:04:23.400 --> 01:04:27.520
[Guest]: would think that after five and a half years of studying to think about you

01:04:27.520 --> 01:04:31.600
[Guest]: know not going back to that and especially in India you people will say

01:04:31.600 --> 01:04:36.040
[Guest]: oh you did medicine and you're not practicing you wasted a seat you know

01:04:36.040 --> 01:04:40.360
[Guest]: government subsidizes your education so much and you're not looking at patients

01:04:40.360 --> 01:04:44.920
[Guest]: and stuff this is the standard thing that I have been facing since then

01:04:44.920 --> 01:04:49.760
[Guest]: because ultimately I didn't get back to practice after that to seeing patients

01:04:49.760 --> 01:04:55.400
[Guest]: and I have the standard retort I say that people who study you know say

01:04:55.400 --> 01:05:00.680
[Guest]: chemical engineering in IIT and then they do like finance in IIM and then they

01:05:00.680 --> 01:05:04.880
[Guest]: start a restaurant so how do you explain those kind of things like even those are

01:05:04.880 --> 01:05:09.600
[Guest]: government subsidized education but no I think medicine is seen with such a kind

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:14.200
[Guest]: of put it on a pedestal and the fact that you are supposed to serve the

01:05:14.200 --> 01:05:20.360
[Guest]: society back because you have wasted a seat in medicine kind of attitude I over

01:05:20.360 --> 01:05:24.040
[Guest]: the years I've gotten used to it and I'm very much in touch with my college

01:05:24.040 --> 01:05:28.400
[Guest]: classmates and on their whatsapp groups and they only keep forwarding silly

01:05:28.400 --> 01:05:34.200
[Guest]: jokes because I think that's their way of coping with life you know like the

01:05:34.200 --> 01:05:40.000
[Guest]: the funny things we see on Twitter are all in those groups and yeah so I think

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:46.200
[Guest]: that's that's how I didn't go back I mean I didn't I didn't quit that stage

01:05:46.200 --> 01:05:49.680
[Guest]: of my life permanently I said I'll see what happens again going with the flow

01:05:49.680 --> 01:05:54.040
[Guest]: attitude but then I did find other interesting things to do and I didn't

01:05:54.040 --> 01:05:59.080
[Guest]: really think that I had to practice medicine just because I had studied that

01:05:59.080 --> 01:06:02.720
[Guest]: knowledge and that kind of processing information and that kind of

01:06:02.720 --> 01:06:07.600
[Guest]: responsibility and dedication and commitment I think those kind of values

01:06:07.600 --> 01:06:13.480
[Guest]: are never going to go away and I'm not going to waste what I learned and I

01:06:13.480 --> 01:06:17.520
[Guest]: definitely I will be in touch with it in one way or the other I'm just not seeing

01:06:17.520 --> 01:06:23.560
[Guest]: patients so I think that's how that whole cycle came around yeah you know

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:26.440
[Amit Varma]: now that you mentioned that incident I remember reading about it in the papers

01:06:26.440 --> 01:06:30.680
[Amit Varma]: in those days and it's it's absolutely kind of horrendous what happened and

01:06:30.680 --> 01:06:35.520
[Amit Varma]: speaking of your erstwhile profession like if there's anyone who has come out

01:06:35.520 --> 01:06:39.080
[Amit Varma]: of you know what has happened in the last few months with any kind of credit

01:06:39.080 --> 01:06:43.000
[Amit Varma]: it's really the frontline healthcare workers and the doctors and the nurses

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:49.640
[Amit Varma]: and I've seen some of that firsthand the kind of thankless work that they sort of

01:06:49.640 --> 01:06:53.640
[Amit Varma]: put in and and what strikes me here is you know that typically before this you

01:06:53.640 --> 01:06:57.640
[Amit Varma]: know the medical profession would kind of get a bad name that oh look it's so

01:06:57.640 --> 01:07:00.960
[Amit Varma]: expensive and they are fleecing and they are making you do all these tests when

01:07:00.960 --> 01:07:04.640
[Amit Varma]: you don't need to and they're all vultures and this and that and where is

01:07:04.640 --> 01:07:09.560
[Amit Varma]: the Hippocratic Oath and yet in these very difficult times it seems to me that

01:07:09.560 --> 01:07:13.840
[Amit Varma]: it's it's fair to say and it's not even sort of a generalization but it's

01:07:13.840 --> 01:07:17.960
[Amit Varma]: absolutely fair to say that the other ones who've stepped up the most and gone

01:07:17.960 --> 01:07:21.600
[Amit Varma]: way beyond the call of duty in you know what they've done though obviously it

01:07:21.600 --> 01:07:25.720
[Amit Varma]: could be selection bias from what I have sort of seen with my own eyes but all

01:07:25.720 --> 01:07:29.400
[Amit Varma]: the reports seem to back up that that's exactly what is happening also it's not

01:07:29.400 --> 01:07:33.440
[Guest]: sorry it's not like they've had a choice also no matter what their own mental

01:07:33.440 --> 01:07:38.840
[Guest]: state and whether they are actually capable of handling this kind of crisis

01:07:38.840 --> 01:07:43.200
[Guest]: like you study medicine but you're not you're you don't expect that you will

01:07:43.200 --> 01:07:46.920
[Guest]: encounter a pandemic in your lifetime because it has not happened in the last

01:07:46.920 --> 01:07:51.400
[Guest]: hundred years and while your life is already stressful and you have these

01:07:51.400 --> 01:07:57.200
[Guest]: emergency night calls but not this 24 by 7 stress where you don't see light at

01:07:57.200 --> 01:08:00.720
[Guest]: the end of the tunnel and you don't know when you can stop going to work and take

01:08:00.720 --> 01:08:05.120
[Guest]: one small break or you can be with your family or you you don't have to be in

01:08:05.120 --> 01:08:10.000
[Guest]: that suffocating PPE so my heart literally goes out and I feel maybe at

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:12.920
[Guest]: this point I feel maybe I took a right decision because I I don't think I

01:08:12.920 --> 01:08:17.640
[Guest]: would have been able to cope with I mean not for the lack of wanting to help

01:08:17.640 --> 01:08:23.760
[Guest]: people but definitely it's not my kind of something that I can bear emotionally

01:08:23.760 --> 01:08:30.560
[Guest]: as well seeing this kind of suffering I can't just take it and not be affected

01:08:30.560 --> 01:08:34.760
[Amit Varma]: by it my my sense is if you were still in the profession you would have stepped

01:08:34.760 --> 01:08:38.640
[Guest]: up and done what you had to do but maybe I think maybe yeah you're right but I

01:08:38.640 --> 01:08:43.280
[Guest]: because I'm not there I feel maybe I would have totally crumbled but when

01:08:43.280 --> 01:08:48.040
[Guest]: you're there that's a that's a different kind of an adrenaline rush and your you

01:08:48.040 --> 01:08:52.080
[Guest]: know dedication that you want to do something for people and I think yeah

01:08:52.080 --> 01:08:55.920
[Guest]: you're right maybe I would have I can't I can't tell now

01:08:55.920 --> 01:08:59.240
[Amit Varma]: No and it's almost dichotomous that I'm struck by like on the one hand you have

01:08:59.240 --> 01:09:02.880
[Amit Varma]: that negative impression of doctors always sort of fleecing patients and

01:09:02.880 --> 01:09:07.120
[Amit Varma]: doing this and doing that and in a sense they're responding to incentives but here

01:09:07.120 --> 01:09:11.320
[Amit Varma]: what what what you what you see a lot of where I think people have gone beyond

01:09:11.320 --> 01:09:14.760
[Amit Varma]: the call of duty in what they have done and typically like I have seen doctors

01:09:14.760 --> 01:09:18.920
[Amit Varma]: and you know people who work in ICUs for example who are just harangued by

01:09:18.920 --> 01:09:24.060
[Amit Varma]: relatives of dead patients and you know who are also obviously upset and they

01:09:24.060 --> 01:09:27.640
[Amit Varma]: are so calm and they deal with it so well and they're just going in there day

01:09:27.640 --> 01:09:31.320
[Amit Varma]: in day out and kind of getting the job done and I don't know what incentives

01:09:31.320 --> 01:09:35.320
[Guest]: function there no incentive is good enough for this it has to come out of

01:09:35.320 --> 01:09:39.840
[Guest]: your own drive because I don't think what can you give to make people go

01:09:39.840 --> 01:09:45.880
[Amit Varma]: through this nothing yeah no no it's it's fantastic but moving on from sort

01:09:45.880 --> 01:09:50.400
[Amit Varma]: of that kind of darker subject you know when you were talking about how other

01:09:50.400 --> 01:09:53.360
[Amit Varma]: professions are allowed to flit all over the place and you said chemical

01:09:53.360 --> 01:09:57.040
[Amit Varma]: engineering and then finance in a bank and then started a restaurant and it

01:09:57.040 --> 01:10:00.240
[Amit Varma]: sounded so incredibly specific that right after this is over I'm gonna

01:10:00.240 --> 01:10:04.280
[Guest]: google if there's no specific I just use this in any kind of co-permutation

01:10:04.280 --> 01:10:09.600
[Amit Varma]: combination I don't have anyone in mind okay we have that disclaimer but

01:10:09.600 --> 01:10:12.760
[Amit Varma]: imagine if there's one poor guy who accidentally happens to fit this in I'm

01:10:12.760 --> 01:10:17.400
[Guest]: not I'm not doing the equivalent of slight reading on a podcast no yes

