[Amit Varma]: to what you mentioned about cooking is it in some way an advantage or does it

01:24:41.920 --> 01:24:45.400
[Amit Varma]: give you a different kind of way at looking at cooking the fact that you

01:24:45.400 --> 01:24:49.280
[Amit Varma]: learned it so late like for example I didn't do economics in college so

01:24:49.280 --> 01:24:52.960
[Amit Varma]: whatever I learned about economics or political philosophy or whatever I

01:24:52.960 --> 01:24:57.120
[Amit Varma]: learned much later in my life and therefore I wasn't bound say by the

01:24:57.120 --> 01:25:01.400
[Amit Varma]: dogmas or the reflexive thinking of whatever the education system might tell

01:25:01.400 --> 01:25:04.800
[Amit Varma]: you so I didn't read only the Keynesians but also the Austrians and also whatever

01:25:04.800 --> 01:25:09.640
[Amit Varma]: and it's kind of broader and I feel that that's kind of an advantage the fact

01:25:09.640 --> 01:25:13.400
[Amit Varma]: that I am learning different things on my own at different points in time and

01:25:13.400 --> 01:25:18.520
[Amit Varma]: all of that going into the prism through which I sort of look at things is in a

01:25:18.520 --> 01:25:22.960
[Amit Varma]: sense an advantage do you feel that in terms of cooking the fact that you know

01:25:22.960 --> 01:25:26.640
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people will learn cooking by just picking up habits when they are

01:25:26.640 --> 01:25:29.960
[Amit Varma]: kids that is go as a banana tea and this is how you do this and this is how you

01:25:29.960 --> 01:25:33.800
[Amit Varma]: do that and you are almost learning everything from scratch right from how

01:25:33.800 --> 01:25:38.360
[Amit Varma]: to turn an oven on and you're learning all the basics from scratch do you feel

01:25:38.360 --> 01:25:43.360
[Amit Varma]: that one that that helped you and made you a little different from you know

01:25:43.360 --> 01:25:47.000
[Amit Varma]: others who might have learned as kids and just internalized a lot of habits

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:51.960
[Amit Varma]: whether good or bad and do you think that it forced you to explicitly think

01:25:51.960 --> 01:25:57.440
[Amit Varma]: about food about the process of cooking and that might have played a part in you

01:25:57.440 --> 01:26:02.040
[Guest]: know what you then went on to become yeah I mean you are right and now that

01:26:02.040 --> 01:26:08.160
[Guest]: you mention it I definitely feel like it did play a part in making me a more

01:26:08.160 --> 01:26:15.760
[Guest]: fearless not bound to rules kind of a cook and I don't believe in like this is

01:26:15.760 --> 01:26:20.720
[Guest]: the hundred percent authentic recipe that I must take to if it tastes good

01:26:20.720 --> 01:26:27.400
[Guest]: it's good and yeah like in having different kinds of combinations which

01:26:27.400 --> 01:26:32.000
[Guest]: traditionally you know we may not be cooking it together or serving two kinds

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:36.120
[Guest]: of dishes together I never had such hang-ups I would cook anything with

01:26:36.120 --> 01:26:41.240
[Guest]: anything a few months ago I had posted this on Twitter like dosa with the

01:26:41.240 --> 01:26:46.280
[Guest]: rajma okay so I got I got trolled by both the South Indians and the North

01:26:46.280 --> 01:26:54.120
[Guest]: Indians how dare you like you know that Greta Thunberg gif how dare you kind of

01:26:54.120 --> 01:26:58.840
[Guest]: thing that people were sending me and which is why I'm not bound to this you

01:26:58.840 --> 01:27:05.200
[Guest]: know I I feel this is a good combination I like it and I'm not following anybody's

01:27:05.200 --> 01:27:10.960
[Guest]: rules not even my grandmother's rules about what to be served with what and I'm

01:27:10.960 --> 01:27:14.560
[Guest]: I'm eating this myself or I'm serving this to my family who don't mind eating

01:27:14.560 --> 01:27:20.320
[Guest]: it so why is it anybody else's problem right so definitely made me a more

01:27:20.320 --> 01:27:25.480
[Guest]: creative cook made me work with a whole lot of different ingredients which I

01:27:25.480 --> 01:27:31.000
[Guest]: found in US at that time and it just kept my mind very open because I had no

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:36.360
[Guest]: set things to follow in the first place like only these vegetables can go into

01:27:36.360 --> 01:27:41.640
[Guest]: sambar or with this sambar only this curry no such hang-ups I like whatever

01:27:41.640 --> 01:27:46.160
[Guest]: is available or whatever I find fascinating and whatever I pick up from

01:27:46.160 --> 01:27:51.560
[Guest]: the shop I would just cook with that I had no plan as such you know I I didn't

01:27:51.560 --> 01:27:57.360
[Guest]: think about this factor at all but definitely I think it played a role in

01:27:57.360 --> 01:28:02.120
[Guest]: how I started cooking and I continue to cook today and you also kind of

01:28:02.120 --> 01:28:05.240
[Amit Varma]: mentioned that you know in your advertising days you know when you were

01:28:05.240 --> 01:28:08.200
[Amit Varma]: writing copy and you were like an in-between between the pharma and the

01:28:08.200 --> 01:28:11.840
[Amit Varma]: marketing people and I guess one of the things you were doing at that time is a

01:28:11.840 --> 01:28:15.840
[Amit Varma]: skill that you practice anyway when it comes to food and is a skill that would

01:28:15.840 --> 01:28:20.520
[Amit Varma]: in some senses have been inherent to you which is that you break down a complex

01:28:20.520 --> 01:28:24.680
[Amit Varma]: idea in simple language and and the thing is when you're to have to do that

01:28:24.680 --> 01:28:28.880
[Amit Varma]: is a great way to even learn about something because if you if you force

01:28:28.880 --> 01:28:32.840
[Amit Varma]: yourself to put something in simple language you are you know and forcing

01:28:32.840 --> 01:28:37.760
[Amit Varma]: yourself to understand it that much better so is that kind of that way of

01:28:37.760 --> 01:28:41.840
[Amit Varma]: thinking that systematic assimilative way of thinking where you know you build

01:28:41.840 --> 01:28:45.920
[Amit Varma]: a base and then you start from there is that something that you feel has always

01:28:45.920 --> 01:28:50.220
[Amit Varma]: been there with you because that's also the approach that you will that you

01:28:50.220 --> 01:28:54.560
[Amit Varma]: bring to your food writing for example that is and I imagine that even when

01:28:54.560 --> 01:28:57.840
[Amit Varma]: you're you know learning Indian classical music that's partly it you

01:28:57.840 --> 01:29:01.160
[Amit Varma]: know you you figure out certain first principles certain rules of the game and

01:29:01.160 --> 01:29:04.760
[Amit Varma]: then you play around with those and then it gets more and more complex but your

01:29:04.760 --> 01:29:09.940
[Amit Varma]: base is very solid at that point so is that kind of explicit thinking something

01:29:09.940 --> 01:29:13.640
[Amit Varma]: that you do for whatever you take up or is it something that you had to do for

01:29:13.640 --> 01:29:17.840
[Amit Varma]: the different things you've taken up what's what's your mindset like because

01:29:17.840 --> 01:29:22.320
[Amit Varma]: it strikes me that a lot of other people who might write about food for example

01:29:22.320 --> 01:29:26.840
[Amit Varma]: will almost you know take an almost intuitive approach to it where it will

01:29:26.840 --> 01:29:31.080
[Amit Varma]: be like you know if they're doing a food review it will almost be like what is

01:29:31.080 --> 01:29:34.760
[Amit Varma]: their sensory experience while you know taking something while I think that you

01:29:34.760 --> 01:29:39.080
[Amit Varma]: know people like you and Krish Ashok who was on the show earlier a kind of more

01:29:39.080 --> 01:29:42.840
[Amit Varma]: methodical thinking a little harder about it tell me a bit about that

01:29:42.840 --> 01:29:46.720
[Amit Varma]: mindset is that something that you've tried to build and cultivate or is that

01:29:46.720 --> 01:29:50.320
[Amit Varma]: even something that in self-reflective moments you've kind of thought about

01:29:50.320 --> 01:29:54.480
[Guest]: when it comes to how you go about your work so like we were discussing earlier

01:29:54.480 --> 01:30:00.920
[Guest]: I value the impact of almost everything that I have done in the past be it

01:30:00.920 --> 01:30:06.280
[Guest]: medical college be it a healthcare advertising or the long stint in

01:30:06.280 --> 01:30:12.240
[Guest]: freelance writing I think everything contributes even without your knowing it

01:30:12.240 --> 01:30:17.840
[Guest]: small bits and pieces towards making you who you are and making your processes

01:30:17.840 --> 01:30:21.680
[Guest]: the way they are when it comes to working so while I definitely like to

01:30:21.680 --> 01:30:27.600
[Guest]: have a very intuitive approach to things like you know we talk about first draft

01:30:27.600 --> 01:30:31.320
[Guest]: second draft my first draft is very stream of consciousness very intuitive I

01:30:31.320 --> 01:30:36.760
[Guest]: don't I don't even think about how is the flow or is it I just put what's on

01:30:36.760 --> 01:30:41.440
[Guest]: my mind and that's what lends that personal touch also and not make it

01:30:41.440 --> 01:30:45.800
[Guest]: sound very like a science project methodical or a science paper kind of a

01:30:45.800 --> 01:30:51.000
[Guest]: writing and then you know thinking about the flow thinking about what more

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:55.360
[Guest]: details could be added what more don't I know about the subject that I need to

01:30:55.360 --> 01:31:00.120
[Guest]: study research a little bit on the side and then come back to add those kind of

01:31:00.120 --> 01:31:03.560
[Guest]: details because it has never happened that I've written on a subject and I

01:31:03.560 --> 01:31:07.680
[Guest]: knew everything about it on day one or when I started writing that I've only

01:31:07.680 --> 01:31:11.880
[Guest]: learned more and more as I've written and you know then that knowledge gets

01:31:11.880 --> 01:31:17.360
[Guest]: applied into the next thing you do so you just gets carried forward and yeah

01:31:17.360 --> 01:31:23.040
[Guest]: so I think it's a combination of both definitely intuitive and because I'm by

01:31:23.040 --> 01:31:27.320
[Guest]: nature very disciplined and I like to have a certain method to doing things

01:31:27.320 --> 01:31:30.960
[Guest]: because I'm also the other extreme where if I don't have a method I can be

01:31:30.960 --> 01:31:35.960
[Guest]: completely mad so for my own sanity I like to keep a certain method you know

01:31:35.960 --> 01:31:40.440
[Guest]: break it down into smaller chunks and make sure I'm able to give my attention

01:31:40.440 --> 01:31:45.120
[Guest]: to every of these little parts of any project that I'm working on so like you

01:31:45.120 --> 01:31:49.960
[Guest]: rightly said even Indian classical music I learned Carnatic for quite a few

01:31:49.960 --> 01:31:53.800
[Guest]: years as a kid and then I think maybe in my adulthood as a rebellion to be

01:31:53.800 --> 01:31:57.560
[Guest]: rebellion to having forced to learn Carnatic music I started learning

01:31:57.560 --> 01:32:03.560
[Guest]: Hindustani classical and it is something I definitely enjoyed more I found that

01:32:03.560 --> 01:32:10.120
[Guest]: there is more scope for creativity and it's a less hard on you with in terms of

01:32:10.120 --> 01:32:13.560
[Guest]: rules and stuff of course there are plenty of rules and I don't even claim

01:32:13.560 --> 01:32:16.800
[Guest]: to know fully well the differences between the two streams even though I've

01:32:16.800 --> 01:32:22.240
[Guest]: learned but you know applying these principles just makes it a little bit

01:32:22.240 --> 01:32:27.320
[Guest]: easier which otherwise a vast subject like this it can feel completely

01:32:27.320 --> 01:32:32.920
[Amit Varma]: difficult to even approach let alone conquer yeah absolutely and and I love

01:32:32.920 --> 01:32:37.200
[Amit Varma]: the phrase that you just used here carry forward it which is such a charmed

01:32:37.200 --> 01:32:42.360
[Guest]: forward Indianism no I'm not making fun of you I think it's a charming phrase

01:32:42.360 --> 01:32:46.560
[Amit Varma]: and language evolves carry forward did so what you what what you also did

01:32:46.560 --> 01:32:50.440
[Amit Varma]: during this time is you also did a diploma or a degree in nutrition I think

01:32:50.440 --> 01:32:57.960
[Guest]: right so tell me a little bit more about that so in 2004 I went to the US for a

01:32:57.960 --> 01:33:03.320
[Guest]: year or so and then I came back to India and the cooking bug had bitten me good

01:33:03.320 --> 01:33:07.640
[Guest]: and proper so I continued you know my biggest worry in coming back to India

01:33:07.640 --> 01:33:11.880
[Guest]: was how am I going to get those ingredients you know and the minute I

01:33:11.880 --> 01:33:17.560
[Guest]: land have to get myself an oven because I wanted to continue that process even

01:33:17.560 --> 01:33:24.320
[Guest]: though I was back home I was back in Bombay and I continued cooking and again

01:33:24.320 --> 01:33:29.000
[Guest]: experimental I had not gained any expertise in just like nine months to

01:33:29.000 --> 01:33:35.240
[Guest]: one year of cooking so you know at those in those days there was some few cooking

01:33:35.240 --> 01:33:41.160
[Guest]: websites like this sify.com Bhavarchi they had one section then like there was

01:33:41.160 --> 01:33:45.040
[Guest]: I think Tarla Dalal had set up a website or I don't remember but there were very

01:33:45.040 --> 01:33:52.080
[Guest]: few cooking websites so you could get recipes from these websites and there

01:33:52.080 --> 01:33:56.280
[Guest]: was my biggest regret was there was no food network in India and there were no

01:33:56.280 --> 01:34:01.200
[Guest]: food good food channels in India and there was no way to get them also but

01:34:01.200 --> 01:34:05.120
[Guest]: anyway I had got enough inspiration from there and I just needed that to keep

01:34:05.120 --> 01:34:09.880
[Guest]: continuing and when I did that I realized that I was so experimental and

01:34:09.880 --> 01:34:13.160
[Guest]: intuitive in my cooking that I could never replicate a dish if it turned out

01:34:13.160 --> 01:34:16.280
[Guest]: good because I didn't even know what I put into it in the first place I would

01:34:16.280 --> 01:34:20.440
[Guest]: just keep putting things as I went right so then I said okay I need to start a

01:34:20.440 --> 01:34:25.960
[Guest]: blog and this is how I will keep everything in one place and I can refer

01:34:25.960 --> 01:34:29.960
[Guest]: to it myself I had no inkling that there was somebody going to search for recipes

01:34:29.960 --> 01:34:33.800
[Guest]: on the web and land up on my blog and I didn't think that was going to happen at

01:34:33.800 --> 01:34:37.400
[Guest]: all but then within a few weeks I got some comments and I realized that

01:34:37.400 --> 01:34:42.360
[Guest]: there's a whole bunch of food bloggers out there mostly Indians in the US they

01:34:42.360 --> 01:34:46.200
[Guest]: were trying to preserve their culture and you know like calling parents and

01:34:46.200 --> 01:34:49.560
[Guest]: taking recipes and putting it down in this permanent kind of format where they

01:34:49.560 --> 01:34:54.320
[Guest]: could access it at any time and which is why I thought oh this is already there

01:34:54.320 --> 01:34:58.360
[Guest]: so I should continue at this and I whatever I would experiment at home I

01:34:58.360 --> 01:35:03.480
[Guest]: would keep posting it on my blog and I think a year passed and I surprisingly

01:35:03.480 --> 01:35:07.960
[Guest]: didn't get bored of it because I would have thought like okay you know blogger

01:35:07.960 --> 01:35:11.960
[Guest]: had a very simple interface like if you could type you could just do it and it

01:35:11.960 --> 01:35:15.840
[Guest]: was easy I kept continuing it at it and then I said okay I think I should

01:35:15.840 --> 01:35:20.680
[Guest]: actually study nutrition properly because in medical school it's hardly

01:35:20.680 --> 01:35:24.640
[Guest]: touched upon although there's one subject called preventive and social

01:35:24.640 --> 01:35:29.320
[Guest]: medicine in the second IBBS but in that it's mostly the preventive disease

01:35:29.320 --> 01:35:33.920
[Guest]: preventing diseases talking about things like polio tuberculosis vaccination

01:35:33.920 --> 01:35:38.800
[Guest]: public health essentially while nutrition should have been integral to

01:35:38.800 --> 01:35:42.880
[Guest]: this topic it wasn't and we hardly touched upon anything like our

01:35:42.880 --> 01:35:47.400
[Guest]: knowledge of nutrition was as good as any layperson's knowledge and I said if

01:35:47.400 --> 01:35:51.760
[Guest]: I'm writing so much about food and now I'm cooking so much I should know a

01:35:51.760 --> 01:35:55.960
[Guest]: little bit more than what I know already so which is why I did this fellowship in

01:35:55.960 --> 01:36:01.600
[Guest]: applied nutrition from Apollo which was a distance come residential kind of a

01:36:01.600 --> 01:36:06.800
[Guest]: course and that helped me a lot in understanding things which I either knew

01:36:06.800 --> 01:36:10.960
[Guest]: very haphazardly or I didn't know about at all so I thought it would be a great

01:36:10.960 --> 01:36:16.880
[Guest]: way to marry the hobby and my qualification and it would just narrow

01:36:16.880 --> 01:36:21.960
[Guest]: the gap and bring it somehow together but I think I'm doing I'm saying all

01:36:21.960 --> 01:36:25.760
[Guest]: this in retrospect I didn't think so much then I just thought this is a good

01:36:25.760 --> 01:36:29.560
[Guest]: idea and I'm learning something so it's not wasted anyway I will put it to use

01:36:29.560 --> 01:36:35.760
[Guest]: and that's when I did that course and then it just you know that that's when I

01:36:35.760 --> 01:36:41.480
[Guest]: started moving the niche of my blog and my writing I started I was a regular

01:36:41.480 --> 01:36:45.560
[Guest]: writer for Men's Health India and I would write mostly on nutrition and

01:36:45.560 --> 01:36:51.840
[Guest]: health related topics and also quite a bit of well-researched things in you

01:36:51.840 --> 01:36:58.160
[Guest]: know nutrition the science of it etc because men's health is a very very

01:36:58.160 --> 01:37:02.840
[Guest]: health focused magazine and you know everything is like proper verified

01:37:02.840 --> 01:37:07.200
[Guest]: information and it's not just saying things which are popular on the internet

01:37:07.200 --> 01:37:13.960
[Guest]: kind of thing so so that that course in nutrition helped me kind of figure out

01:37:13.960 --> 01:37:19.800
[Guest]: what I want my focus to be over the next years and it also helped because I was

01:37:19.800 --> 01:37:25.080
[Guest]: cooking a lot I was getting a lot more interested in food and you know I would

01:37:25.080 --> 01:37:30.280
[Guest]: want to call friends home so I could try out different things and make lots of

01:37:30.280 --> 01:37:34.160
[Guest]: food and serve people because otherwise it's just my husband and me how much are

01:37:34.160 --> 01:37:38.640
[Guest]: we going to cook and eat I would look forward to these you know calling people

01:37:38.640 --> 01:37:44.400
[Guest]: over and yeah so I think that that was the other turning point actually

01:37:44.400 --> 01:37:52.080
[Guest]: focusing on nutrition and whereby using my education in somewhat a good way

01:37:52.080 --> 01:37:56.680
[Guest]: where I can contribute my knowledge of you know the human body physiology

01:37:56.680 --> 01:38:02.440
[Guest]: biochemistry everything and nutrition coming together nicely and it kind of

01:38:02.440 --> 01:38:06.040
[Amit Varma]: strikes me that the science of nutrition is a bit of a contrast to the science of

01:38:06.040 --> 01:38:09.800
[Amit Varma]: medicine for example in the sense that the science of medicine you know what

01:38:09.800 --> 01:38:12.480
[Amit Varma]: you know is what you know and of course there are things you don't know and you

01:38:12.480 --> 01:38:16.280
[Amit Varma]: find out more about them but as far as what you know is concerned it's fairly

01:38:16.280 --> 01:38:21.000
[Amit Varma]: settled it will evolve in terms of going deeper but you're not going to find that

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:25.160
[Amit Varma]: what you thought was a fundamental truth is completely false while I think in

01:38:25.160 --> 01:38:29.120
[Amit Varma]: nutrition in a sense that has kind of happened like one of my pet themes and

01:38:29.120 --> 01:38:34.840
[Amit Varma]: it's a surprise I haven't really done an episode on it is you know how America's

01:38:34.840 --> 01:38:40.120
[Amit Varma]: obesity epidemic was actually caused by the state where for decades we had this

01:38:40.120 --> 01:38:45.000
[Amit Varma]: impression that sugar is fine and fat is evil while in recent times we have

01:38:45.000 --> 01:38:48.560
[Amit Varma]: realized that that's absolutely not true and for those who are further interested

01:38:48.560 --> 01:38:52.480
[Amit Varma]: you know there's a great book by Gary Taubes called the case against sugar

01:38:52.480 --> 01:38:55.520
[Amit Varma]: there's a great book by Nina Tycoles called the big fat surprise I'll link

01:38:55.520 --> 01:39:00.360
[Amit Varma]: them from the show notes I think Tycoles also did a good episode with Joe Rogan

01:39:00.360 --> 01:39:05.120
[Amit Varma]: on them but the TLDR of that or what fundamentally happened is that these

01:39:05.120 --> 01:39:09.080
[Amit Varma]: cases were made to find out more about heart disease these studies were done

01:39:09.080 --> 01:39:13.000
[Amit Varma]: rather to find out more about heart disease in the 50s and 60s and they were

01:39:13.000 --> 01:39:16.400
[Amit Varma]: funded by the sugar lobby you know the methodology was suspect and they made

01:39:16.400 --> 01:39:20.480
[Amit Varma]: fat the big villain and absorbed sugar while today we know that fundamentally

01:39:20.480 --> 01:39:25.560
[Amit Varma]: sugar is poison certainly in certain forms and you know in processed foods

01:39:25.560 --> 01:39:29.600
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth so it's very interesting that it's you know on the

01:39:29.600 --> 01:39:32.360
[Amit Varma]: one hand you do medicine where the science is kind of settled but on the

01:39:32.360 --> 01:39:35.640
[Amit Varma]: other hand you're doing nutrition where it seems like the whole world is being

01:39:35.640 --> 01:39:40.760
[Amit Varma]: upended every two years and there are more and more sort of new things coming

01:39:40.760 --> 01:39:45.160
[Amit Varma]: out how does one then cope with that because then the concept of healthy

01:39:45.160 --> 01:39:49.080
[Amit Varma]: changes a little bit like when I was growing up I remembered at fatty foods

01:39:49.080 --> 01:39:52.640
[Amit Varma]: weren't good you know even when it came to meats people were moving to leaner

01:39:52.640 --> 01:39:57.120
[Amit Varma]: meats which we now know is completely unnecessary and at the same time you

01:39:57.120 --> 01:40:01.680
[Amit Varma]: know it was okay to drink coke and and you know with all its many spoons of

01:40:01.680 --> 01:40:05.520
[Amit Varma]: sugar or whatever it is which is just insane and you've got a nice little

01:40:05.520 --> 01:40:10.600
[Amit Varma]: screed against processed foods in your book so tell me a little bit about how

01:40:10.600 --> 01:40:14.520
[Amit Varma]: you're thinking of nutrition evolved in this period of time because there are

01:40:14.520 --> 01:40:18.400
[Amit Varma]: also so many fads and fashions going on and it's almost like different

01:40:18.400 --> 01:40:23.840
[Amit Varma]: ideological camps form around these things so when when you so what was your

01:40:23.840 --> 01:40:27.720
[Amit Varma]: what's your take on this what was your approach of all this you're right

01:40:27.720 --> 01:40:33.400
[Guest]: because you know study of disease and the study of nutrition are like

01:40:33.400 --> 01:40:38.440
[Guest]: completely different things happening and definitely there has been more

01:40:38.440 --> 01:40:43.880
[Guest]: funding and more priority to the study of disease because you can save lives

01:40:43.880 --> 01:40:48.800
[Guest]: whereas studying nutrition it's more like you're preventing something so it

01:40:48.800 --> 01:40:54.080
[Guest]: definitely gets a little less or much less importance than the study or funding

01:40:54.080 --> 01:40:58.640
[Guest]: of disease but then who funds the nutrition studies it is mostly lobbies

01:40:58.640 --> 01:41:04.080
[Guest]: be it like the sugar lobby or the wheat growing lobby or the dairy lobby right

01:41:04.080 --> 01:41:10.560
[Guest]: so I have I've heard about this in the US that if a certain lobby is funding a

01:41:10.560 --> 01:41:16.680
[Guest]: study you can be like 75% sure that that study will only bring about the points

01:41:16.680 --> 01:41:20.400
[Guest]: that are favorable to the lobby who funded them isn't that obvious because

01:41:20.400 --> 01:41:25.520
[Guest]: there is such a conflict of interest if someone is paying me one crore to say

01:41:25.520 --> 01:41:29.520
[Guest]: find out about this but they are themselves a sugar company how can I

01:41:29.520 --> 01:41:35.120
[Guest]: come out and say that sugar is bad right so I think believing in such studies you

01:41:35.120 --> 01:41:38.960
[Guest]: should also know who has funded these studies in the first place because that

01:41:38.960 --> 01:41:44.160
[Guest]: also impacts to a great extent what the result of that study turns out to be you

01:41:44.160 --> 01:41:50.880
[Guest]: know I think treating health is just the absence of disease and therefore not

01:41:50.880 --> 01:41:56.320
[Guest]: giving nutrition an important role is also very what do you say it's not a

01:41:56.320 --> 01:42:03.080
[Guest]: good thing because I think preventing is much easier it costs less and it's more

01:42:03.080 --> 01:42:08.160
[Guest]: sustainable in the long run and you can just do it by making these small changes

01:42:08.160 --> 01:42:12.520
[Guest]: in your day-to-day life rather than someone who has to literally flush down

01:42:12.520 --> 01:42:17.120
[Guest]: his entire life savings to do a like a bypass surgery or undergo like a

01:42:17.120 --> 01:42:23.080
[Guest]: dialysis every two weeks so I think we need to step back and we need to stop

01:42:23.080 --> 01:42:27.720
[Guest]: thinking about health only when we fall sick you know in in traditional Chinese

01:42:27.720 --> 01:42:33.040
[Guest]: medicine I had read about this thing where the emperors would pay a retainer

01:42:33.040 --> 01:42:37.360
[Guest]: to the physicians the traditional Chinese medicine physicians and the

01:42:37.360 --> 01:42:41.560
[Guest]: minute they fell sick they would not pay them because they are paying them to

01:42:41.560 --> 01:42:47.200
[Guest]: keep them healthy not to treat them when they fell sick so if the Emperor or

01:42:47.200 --> 01:42:50.640
[Guest]: their family the royal family fell sick they would not get paid for that month

01:42:50.640 --> 01:42:57.840
[Guest]: so it's it's the reverse right and that is the importance of something like a

01:42:57.840 --> 01:43:04.880
[Guest]: nutrition or your lifestyle where little steps matter a lot and what you can do

01:43:04.880 --> 01:43:09.400
[Guest]: on a daily basis and that is exactly in contrast from some of these fads and the

01:43:09.400 --> 01:43:15.800
[Guest]: camps that you were talking about where I can't think of any fad or a kind of a

01:43:15.800 --> 01:43:21.440
[Guest]: you know a diet a diet that excludes a lot of foods a diet that deprives people

01:43:21.440 --> 01:43:26.440
[Guest]: you can't possibly do it all your life and because there are a lot of other

01:43:26.440 --> 01:43:31.520
[Guest]: factors that play a role in what you eat your emotional state your family your

01:43:31.520 --> 01:43:37.080
[Guest]: socio-economic status and something like nutrition is impacted by so many factors

01:43:37.080 --> 01:43:42.120
[Guest]: and it is not easy to just put a label and say that you do this diet and you

01:43:42.120 --> 01:43:47.200
[Guest]: will lose you know 10 kilos of weight and that is the kind of oversimplified

01:43:47.200 --> 01:43:52.040
[Guest]: information that is actually so much in vogue these days people just want

01:43:52.040 --> 01:43:57.320
[Guest]: binaries are you vegan are you like meat eating is meat good is vegan good there

01:43:57.320 --> 01:44:02.120
[Guest]: are no simple answers to this and nutrition see health itself is a

01:44:02.120 --> 01:44:05.800
[Guest]: medicine and health is a very complicated science you're dealing with

01:44:05.800 --> 01:44:10.520
[Guest]: the human body and every human body is different and in a space like nutrition

01:44:10.520 --> 01:44:15.920
[Guest]: where there's even much less research and there are so many it's like in

01:44:15.920 --> 01:44:19.440
[Guest]: mathematical terms it's like a multivariable problem where what

01:44:19.440 --> 01:44:23.240
[Guest]: variable are you going to fix to understand what is the thing right and

01:44:23.240 --> 01:44:28.640
[Guest]: someone may spend 20 years researching on where the maximum antioxidants are in

01:44:28.640 --> 01:44:34.240
[Guest]: a grape and they find it that it's on the surface of the seed and you know we

01:44:34.240 --> 01:44:38.440
[Guest]: are all eating seedless grapes these days but you find that and another one

01:44:38.440 --> 01:44:42.440
[Guest]: year somebody else comes and says no no it's actually in the pulp so it's like

01:44:42.440 --> 01:44:47.840
[Guest]: things like you said things change so rapidly so then are we supposed to keep

01:44:47.840 --> 01:44:52.200
[Guest]: reading and updating ourselves on every such research paper or sometimes just

01:44:52.200 --> 01:44:56.880
[Guest]: follow some absolute basic rules like eating whole foods eating in moderation

01:44:56.880 --> 01:45:01.800
[Guest]: not eating too much like not stuffing yourself until you're 100% full and

01:45:01.800 --> 01:45:06.000
[Guest]: therefore eating slowly so you realize when you're full you know eating in a

01:45:06.000 --> 01:45:11.120
[Guest]: pleasant setup where you're eating mindfully so these are the things that

01:45:11.120 --> 01:45:15.080
[Guest]: you can never go wrong with and no paper is going to come out tomorrow and tell

01:45:15.080 --> 01:45:19.400
[Guest]: you that you ate a little less so you know you have created space for this

01:45:19.400 --> 01:45:23.260
[Guest]: disease in your life that's never going to happen so why not follow the

01:45:23.260 --> 01:45:27.560
[Guest]: principles that you know for certain are not going to change like if you if

01:45:27.560 --> 01:45:31.400
[Guest]: someone eats one or two eggs in a day that's not going to kill them so don't

01:45:31.400 --> 01:45:35.480
[Guest]: do anything extreme and I think the biggest problem in today's times is that

01:45:35.480 --> 01:45:41.240
[Guest]: the more polarized you are in any field that you're more in news and the people

01:45:41.240 --> 01:45:45.680
[Guest]: will lap up your information immediately but the minute you are very moderate and

01:45:45.680 --> 01:45:50.480
[Guest]: you don't have that extreme bone in you you don't people say what is this so

01:45:50.480 --> 01:45:55.040
[Guest]: boring like it being in between is the worst place to be because you'll get no

01:45:55.040 --> 01:46:00.320
[Amit Varma]: attention but see Nandita yeah you are the kind of person on Twitter that they

01:46:00.320 --> 01:46:06.600
[Amit Varma]: would call you a centrist when it comes to food as a pejorative but no no sorry

01:46:06.600 --> 01:46:13.480
[Guest]: I interrupted you finish I was pretty much done yeah I think that that's what

01:46:13.480 --> 01:46:18.720
[Guest]: I wanted to say that you know also things like gut microbe for example that

01:46:18.720 --> 01:46:25.920
[Guest]: it's like 37 trillions of gut microbes and is it even possible that even in a

01:46:25.920 --> 01:46:30.440
[Guest]: century we'll do enough research to understand what impact this has on our

01:46:30.440 --> 01:46:35.480
[Guest]: body but we do know certain things for sure that you know gut microbes

01:46:35.480 --> 01:46:39.880
[Guest]: influence your immunity because they talk to your immune system gut microbes

01:46:39.880 --> 01:46:43.560
[Guest]: influence your mental health you know gut microbes influence a lot of

01:46:43.560 --> 01:46:48.200
[Guest]: functions in your body which still cannot be specified or list put down in

01:46:48.200 --> 01:46:52.880
[Guest]: a listicle but what is known is that when you eat you're literally feeding

01:46:52.880 --> 01:46:57.160
[Guest]: your gut microbes you're not feeding yourself because whatever the stuff that

01:46:57.160 --> 01:47:01.920
[Guest]: your body hasn't digested these are the guys that are going to digest all of

01:47:01.920 --> 01:47:06.400
[Guest]: that and then release the byproducts which then benefits you in so many

01:47:06.400 --> 01:47:11.800
[Guest]: different ways like head to toe it's affecting your body so to think of the

01:47:11.800 --> 01:47:16.320
[Guest]: science is so complex and so fascinating but even by just following some very

01:47:16.320 --> 01:47:20.480
[Guest]: basic general principles having this background knowledge but doing simple

01:47:20.480 --> 01:47:24.200
[Guest]: things which you know for certain will have positive impact in your life I

01:47:24.200 --> 01:47:28.240
[Amit Varma]: think that is very important yeah in fact you know people say we were

01:47:28.240 --> 01:47:33.840
[Amit Varma]: colonized by the British no we are colonized by our gut microbes and just

01:47:33.840 --> 01:47:36.800
[Amit Varma]: to sort of elaborate on a thought which I kind of left halfway about how the

01:47:36.800 --> 01:47:40.880
[Amit Varma]: state caused the obesity epidemic the thing is after all these studies came

01:47:40.880 --> 01:47:46.080
[Amit Varma]: out in the 50s and the 60s in the late 1970s the US Health Association whatever

01:47:46.080 --> 01:47:49.440
[Amit Varma]: they are called I forget the official name came out with a series of dietary

01:47:49.440 --> 01:47:52.800
[Amit Varma]: guidelines on what you should eat and what you should not eat and they got it

01:47:52.800 --> 01:47:56.960
[Amit Varma]: completely wrong and if you look at the graph of America's obesity epidemic it

01:47:56.960 --> 01:48:02.040
[Amit Varma]: kind of begins from there and of course sugar is a big problem I wasn't keto for

01:48:02.040 --> 01:48:05.600
[Amit Varma]: a while and it really worked for me but then I kind of went off and I sort of

01:48:05.600 --> 01:48:08.960
[Amit Varma]: went back but it worked for me except that you know in India it's kind of hard

01:48:08.960 --> 01:48:13.680
[Amit Varma]: to keep a keto diet because you are surrounded by biryani and dosa and so on

01:48:13.680 --> 01:48:18.640
[Amit Varma]: so what do you do and I also agree about not getting too alarmed by whatever the

01:48:18.640 --> 01:48:22.480
[Amit Varma]: fad of the day might be like I saw the headline a few months ago saying bacon

01:48:22.480 --> 01:48:25.920
[Amit Varma]: causes cancer and that was too much for me I was like let it cause cancer I'm

01:48:25.920 --> 01:48:29.440
[Amit Varma]: not going to stop having bacon for God's sake and by the way you mentioned gut

01:48:29.440 --> 01:48:32.720
[Amit Varma]: there's a lovely book I'd read a few years back called gut by Julia Enders

01:48:32.720 --> 01:48:37.920
[Amit Varma]: which was a fascinating book on the effect of the gut on our physical and

01:48:37.920 --> 01:48:41.760
[Amit Varma]: mental health so I'll link that from the show notes as well let's go on to your

01:48:41.760 --> 01:48:46.240
[Amit Varma]: book because one of the early things that you write in your fine book is

01:48:46.240 --> 01:48:50.440
[Amit Varma]: where you talk about the virtue of the diet of our grandparents like you quote

01:48:50.440 --> 01:48:53.800
[Amit Varma]: Michael Pollan saying quote don't eat anything your great-great-great

01:48:53.800 --> 01:48:58.680
[Amit Varma]: grandmother wouldn't recognize as food stop quote and then you have this nice

01:48:58.680 --> 01:49:03.720
[Amit Varma]: section on what your maternal great-grandparents actually ate and why

01:49:03.720 --> 01:49:07.240
[Amit Varma]: and what their routines were like tell me a little bit about that because that

01:49:07.240 --> 01:49:12.800
[Guest]: was also quite instructive for me so you know Michael Pollan's that quote is

01:49:12.800 --> 01:49:17.400
[Guest]: obviously very very very famous almost everybody has heard of it but it's also

01:49:17.400 --> 01:49:22.880
[Guest]: a bit extreme and it's not really it's not possible to follow it 200% in

01:49:22.880 --> 01:49:28.640
[Guest]: today's times because we're not 200 years earlier we are in 2021 and we will

01:49:28.640 --> 01:49:31.720
[Guest]: be influenced by the things that are happening now the things that are

01:49:31.720 --> 01:49:38.080
[Guest]: available now the way our life is now so we can't really go back in time and eat

01:49:38.080 --> 01:49:43.160
[Guest]: what exactly they ate but I think it's worthwhile just catching the the

01:49:43.160 --> 01:49:48.040
[Guest]: sentiment behind that statement where if you have to choose between two kinds of

01:49:48.040 --> 01:49:51.800
[Guest]: foods there should be enough knowledge that you're choosing something that is

01:49:51.800 --> 01:49:56.200
[Guest]: lesser processed and there is knowledge everywhere but once you keep putting

01:49:56.200 --> 01:50:00.280
[Guest]: this into practice every single day which might feel a bit tough initially

01:50:00.280 --> 01:50:03.920
[Guest]: but when you put this into practice every day it just becomes second nature

01:50:03.920 --> 01:50:09.080
[Guest]: and you know that that knowledge becomes the way you deal with every little food

01:50:09.080 --> 01:50:12.680
[Guest]: confusion that you have in your life because you know like there's this nice

01:50:12.680 --> 01:50:16.600
[Guest]: saying which I read somewhere three times a day you get to choose what you're

01:50:16.600 --> 01:50:20.080
[Guest]: going to put inside your body and how you're going to impact your health so

01:50:20.080 --> 01:50:26.760
[Guest]: make it worthwhile it's very simple like say I have to choose between say you

01:50:26.760 --> 01:50:33.000
[Guest]: know a banana and a banana bread even a kid knows that a banana is closer to the

01:50:33.000 --> 01:50:37.280
[Guest]: way nature made it than banana bread which has added flour sugar baking

01:50:37.280 --> 01:50:43.860
[Guest]: powder salt eggs everything right fat and it's it's cooked at a high heat so

01:50:43.860 --> 01:50:49.520
[Guest]: it's baked just eating the banana would have been far simpler but here we are in

01:50:49.520 --> 01:50:54.160
[Guest]: the times when we are like banana bread addition to with the pandemic you know

01:50:54.160 --> 01:50:58.680
[Guest]: having restarted and we're all making banana bread as something like a comfort

01:50:58.680 --> 01:51:03.600
[Guest]: food because banana as a fruit doesn't hit that spot as a comfort food it

01:51:03.600 --> 01:51:09.400
[Guest]: doesn't have the added sugar added fats added carbs which is what qualifies to

01:51:09.400 --> 01:51:13.520
[Guest]: make it as a comfort food and it ticks all those boxes to make us feel good so

01:51:13.520 --> 01:51:18.640
[Guest]: there's this whole emotional aspect also like given the times we are facing now

01:51:18.640 --> 01:51:23.360
[Guest]: we are having two kinds of behavior either there are people chugging liters

01:51:23.360 --> 01:51:28.560
[Guest]: of cada and eating like a vitamin C going out of stock on Amazon people are

01:51:28.560 --> 01:51:33.720
[Guest]: eating zinc and vitamin C tablets and the others are just saying chug this I'm

01:51:33.720 --> 01:51:37.160
[Guest]: just having to stay sane in these times I'm going to eat whatever makes me

01:51:37.160 --> 01:51:41.160
[Guest]: happy I'm not even stepping out so my weight is the last thing on my mind I

01:51:41.160 --> 01:51:45.120
[Guest]: just need to eat something that makes me feel good and both these lines of

01:51:45.120 --> 01:51:49.320
[Guest]: thought are right for the times that we are now you know so it's very difficult

01:51:49.320 --> 01:51:54.160
[Guest]: to just tell people that hey these are the rules follow it and don't eat

01:51:54.160 --> 01:52:00.280
[Guest]: unprocessed at all but we need to have a decent enough inherent knowledge of what

01:52:00.280 --> 01:52:04.200
[Guest]: is good for us and put that into practice in our day-to-day life whenever

01:52:04.200 --> 01:52:08.960
[Guest]: possible and not really beat ourself up for the times like these when you know

01:52:08.960 --> 01:52:13.280
[Guest]: this is the last thing on our mind right now and we just want to we have we are

01:52:13.280 --> 01:52:18.800
[Guest]: in that survival instinct where neither are we worried about our weight nor are

01:52:18.800 --> 01:52:24.120
[Guest]: we worried about the impact of some chips that I'm going to eat now or I'm

01:52:24.120 --> 01:52:29.840
[Guest]: thinking of eating it in a raw state no because even like so many people even in

01:52:29.840 --> 01:52:34.200
[Guest]: the wellness scene world over have said that they have been eating a lot of

01:52:34.200 --> 01:52:38.320
[Guest]: sugar they've been eating a lot of carbs in the last one year can't blame

01:52:38.320 --> 01:52:41.800
[Guest]: ourselves for that because that's the way the times are and that's how we are

01:52:41.800 --> 01:52:46.580
[Guest]: trying to cope with that so that is also fine but overall you should know what is

01:52:46.580 --> 01:52:51.440
[Guest]: good for you and you know regarding yeah my great-grandparents I really found it

01:52:51.440 --> 01:52:56.720
[Guest]: fascinating when I made that comparison between what we do and you know what

01:52:56.720 --> 01:53:00.680
[Guest]: I've seen my great-grandparents the way they eat and even much later when there

01:53:00.680 --> 01:53:03.920
[Guest]: was a telephone at home they would actually keep the telephone off hook

01:53:03.920 --> 01:53:08.760
[Guest]: during lunchtime because they don't want to be disturbed by phone calls and today

01:53:08.760 --> 01:53:12.480
[Guest]: we are actually having the mobile phone in our hand and scrolling down and

01:53:12.480 --> 01:53:18.000
[Guest]: seeing what's going on like we we want to be disturbed right and we have gone

01:53:18.000 --> 01:53:21.300
[Guest]: to the other extreme and sometimes they would forget to put the phone back on

01:53:21.300 --> 01:53:24.720
[Guest]: hook even until 4 o'clock and and because they were growing old we would

01:53:24.720 --> 01:53:27.680
[Guest]: like be you know getting mad at them like what is this they're forever

01:53:27.680 --> 01:53:32.640
[Guest]: forgetting to put this back on hook but that was their dedication to the ritual

01:53:32.640 --> 01:53:38.200
[Guest]: of eating even the most basic simple meal where they didn't know superfoods

01:53:38.200 --> 01:53:41.520
[Guest]: they didn't know what they would buy what was cheap what was in season and

01:53:41.520 --> 01:53:47.440
[Guest]: what was available in their local market and you know they all lived up to 90 and

01:53:47.440 --> 01:53:52.880
[Guest]: touch wood like no ailments or anything so I have seen that firsthand and the

01:53:52.880 --> 01:53:58.320
[Guest]: same with my grandparents the kind of dedication and creating a ritual around

01:53:58.320 --> 01:54:04.640
[Guest]: eating and having a calm scenario and you know having that respectful

01:54:04.640 --> 01:54:09.840
[Guest]: atmosphere towards your food and not just gulping it down so I read this

01:54:09.840 --> 01:54:16.200
[Guest]: interesting thing in B Wilson's book called the way we eat where she quotes

01:54:16.200 --> 01:54:22.320
[Guest]: this study done on 4,000 Japanese men who live in the US and they were all

01:54:22.320 --> 01:54:26.800
[Guest]: above 30 years of age and they wanted to compare that you know even though they

01:54:26.800 --> 01:54:31.840
[Guest]: are eating Japanese food how does their heart disease incidence etc compare with

01:54:31.840 --> 01:54:36.060
[Guest]: the men living in Japan and eating Japanese food and even though these

01:54:36.060 --> 01:54:40.960
[Guest]: people living in the US were eating Japanese food their heart disease rates

01:54:40.960 --> 01:54:45.520
[Guest]: were fivefold as compared to the ones in Japan why because they didn't have that

01:54:45.520 --> 01:54:50.760
[Guest]: slow culture they didn't have that sense of attachment towards their food setting

01:54:50.760 --> 01:54:55.840
[Guest]: up everything nicely grab and this the whole American attitude of being rushed

01:54:55.840 --> 01:55:00.760
[Guest]: and grab and go in a hurry and you know the impatience and urgency around food

01:55:00.760 --> 01:55:06.160
[Guest]: versus the slower rhythms and the rituals of eating in Japan you know

01:55:06.160 --> 01:55:09.800
[Guest]: though they were eating the same food they still showed where everything else

01:55:09.800 --> 01:55:15.160
[Guest]: was constant they still showed fivefold increase in things like heart disease so

01:55:15.160 --> 01:55:20.520
[Guest]: it just goes to show that how we eat is a lot lot more important than what we

01:55:20.520 --> 01:55:25.360
[Guest]: eat and sometimes we don't even focus on what we eat so let alone how we eat

01:55:25.360 --> 01:55:30.200
[Guest]: that's like the next step right so we need to not just understand what is it

01:55:30.200 --> 01:55:33.960
[Guest]: that we're eating but we also need to understand how are we eating are we

01:55:33.960 --> 01:55:38.360
[Guest]: eating mindfully and you know are we having that kind of relationship with

01:55:38.360 --> 01:55:43.720
[Guest]: food where it's not over guilt or hate or emotions or boredom but you're eating

01:55:43.720 --> 01:55:47.960
[Guest]: to nourish yourself and it's it's a very healthy relationship yeah there's a

01:55:47.960 --> 01:55:53.520
[Amit Varma]: there's a lot of fascinating stuff to unpack them I mean it strikes me that in

01:55:53.520 --> 01:55:57.560
[Amit Varma]: modern times we are really fighting of a competition between two competing

01:55:57.560 --> 01:56:01.200
[Amit Varma]: addictions or perhaps two cooperating addictions one is to carbs and one is to

01:56:01.200 --> 01:56:05.160
[Amit Varma]: social media which is why we are eating lots and lots of carbs while staring at

01:56:05.160 --> 01:56:09.760
[Amit Varma]: our smartphones I mean I was in keto a couple of years back and I lost almost

01:56:09.760 --> 01:56:15.320
[Amit Varma]: 20 kgs and felt incredibly healthy and no brain fog and so on and it was pretty

01:56:15.320 --> 01:56:18.920
[Amit Varma]: amazing but this year I have completely you know you described the kind of

01:56:18.920 --> 01:56:23.120
[Amit Varma]: person who's just ordering comfort food all the time so I've finished my biryani

01:56:23.120 --> 01:56:28.120
[Amit Varma]: phase thankfully that seems to be behind me but now I'm in my pizza phase so God

01:56:28.120 --> 01:56:32.480
[Amit Varma]: knows where this is going and definitely at my heaviest ever now a couple of sort

01:56:32.480 --> 01:56:36.520
[Amit Varma]: of questions that emerge out of what you said and again staying on the

01:56:36.520 --> 01:56:41.840
[Amit Varma]: grandparents seem because that seems to me to be an interesting dining table to

01:56:41.840 --> 01:56:45.880
[Amit Varma]: use as a prism for looking at our own dining tables in in different ways and

01:56:45.880 --> 01:56:49.560
[Amit Varma]: one of those ways is mindfulness like very often when I'm eating even if I've

01:56:49.560 --> 01:56:53.440
[Amit Varma]: ordered something that I really love eating or you know if I've cooked

01:56:53.440 --> 01:56:57.880
[Amit Varma]: something I love eating like I make the best bacon and egg fried rice in India

01:56:57.880 --> 01:57:02.640
[Amit Varma]: but even when I'm having food that I love you know I'm only focused on the

01:57:02.640 --> 01:57:07.080
[Amit Varma]: taste for maybe the first 20-30 seconds after that I'm lost in my smartphone or

01:57:07.080 --> 01:57:10.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm reading something or maybe I'm lost in my thoughts and it's all kind of gone

01:57:10.880 --> 01:57:15.160
[Amit Varma]: and I'm not thinking about my food at all I'm gulping it down I'm definitely

01:57:15.160 --> 01:57:19.480
[Amit Varma]: not chewing as much as I'm supposed to chew and all of that and this is

01:57:19.480 --> 01:57:24.200
[Amit Varma]: something that kind of baffles me that I love food you know taste matters to me

01:57:24.200 --> 01:57:28.560
[Amit Varma]: you know I like specific things and I don't like other things but sometimes I

01:57:28.560 --> 01:57:33.040
[Amit Varma]: will be I will have finished a meal without even having focused on it for a

01:57:33.040 --> 01:57:36.720
[Amit Varma]: single moment you know and I'm looking back at my childhood and I'm can't

01:57:36.720 --> 01:57:40.600
[Amit Varma]: recall what it was like were we more mindful than like I can totally

01:57:40.600 --> 01:57:44.720
[Amit Varma]: imagine taking the phone off the hook because you want it to be an experience

01:57:44.720 --> 01:57:47.680
[Amit Varma]: where you're interacting with your family and you don't have four people

01:57:47.680 --> 01:57:51.160
[Amit Varma]: sitting together but at the same time sitting separately because there's a

01:57:51.160 --> 01:57:55.320
[Amit Varma]: screen in front of them have we become less mindful of our food what do you

01:57:55.320 --> 01:57:58.680
[Amit Varma]: remember from your personal memories and is this something that you tell yourself

01:57:58.680 --> 01:58:02.680
[Amit Varma]: when you sit down to eat that I'm going to focus on the taste now that I'm going

01:58:02.680 --> 01:58:06.600
[Amit Varma]: to actually do you have to force yourself to do that number one and

01:58:06.600 --> 01:58:10.960
[Amit Varma]: number two if you were to sort of make a normative judgment on this is this bad

01:58:10.960 --> 01:58:17.760
[Amit Varma]: is not being mindful while eating bad and if so why I just address the thing

01:58:17.760 --> 01:58:22.720
[Guest]: you asked last first and then go back into the question see it is bad for a

01:58:22.720 --> 01:58:29.640
[Guest]: few reasons the most obvious being that we are consuming calories or food in

01:58:29.640 --> 01:58:34.480
[Guest]: some form and we are not enjoying that and we are not putting our mind into it

01:58:34.480 --> 01:58:39.120
[Guest]: and at the end of it we don't even know sometimes if have we eaten it or not

01:58:39.120 --> 01:58:44.440
[Guest]: because we have been so absent from the whole process of eating and the other

01:58:44.440 --> 01:58:48.560
[Guest]: problem this leads to is that you know even satiety is in a way linked to this

01:58:48.560 --> 01:58:53.640
[Guest]: so if your mind has not been in the process your body may not even realize

01:58:53.640 --> 01:58:57.560
[Guest]: that hey I've eaten so you may end up eating again something very soon because

01:58:57.560 --> 01:59:01.720
[Guest]: forget the digestion your mind has not digested the fact that you have eaten

01:59:01.720 --> 01:59:06.400
[Guest]: that food and in a way one doesn't end up consuming more calories because

01:59:06.400 --> 01:59:11.000
[Guest]: invariably when we are not focused on our eating process because it takes 20

01:59:11.000 --> 01:59:15.080
[Guest]: minutes for the stomach to send the signal to the brain that it's full but

01:59:15.080 --> 01:59:18.680
[Guest]: if we have finished our whole food in five minutes then where is the time to

01:59:18.680 --> 01:59:24.400
[Guest]: understand how full or how not full are we I was doing intermittent fasting for

01:59:24.400 --> 01:59:28.040
[Guest]: a very long time and it helped me a great deal but I had to stop because I

01:59:28.040 --> 01:59:32.560
[Guest]: started getting like excruciating headaches and I was not I was not able

01:59:32.560 --> 01:59:37.560
[Guest]: to do it anymore but I realized when I started fasting that how hunger feels

01:59:37.560 --> 01:59:43.080
[Guest]: you know because we are so used to being surrounded by food all the time and

01:59:43.080 --> 01:59:48.000
[Guest]: especially being someone who is in the food space and I'm constantly cooking

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:53.520
[Guest]: tasting you know and I've never been religious so I have never done a

01:59:53.520 --> 01:59:58.560
[Guest]: religious fast in my life and this is what I felt okay this is how hunger

01:59:58.560 --> 02:00:04.840
[Guest]: feels like and just to experience hunger was like a miracle because we you know

02:00:04.840 --> 02:00:09.000
[Guest]: in our privileged setup we never experience hunger before we feel hungry

02:00:09.000 --> 02:00:13.720
[Guest]: we've already eaten something right and very rarely if we've gone out especially

02:00:13.720 --> 02:00:17.320
[Guest]: in Bangalore scenario and you got stuck in traffic for two hours and then you

02:00:17.320 --> 02:00:21.720
[Guest]: come back home really hungry but that's like a forced situation you've never

02:00:21.720 --> 02:00:26.480
[Guest]: done it voluntarily so I think just experiencing what hunger feels like

02:00:26.480 --> 02:00:31.880
[Guest]: experiencing what full feels like we don't unless we pay attention to our

02:00:31.880 --> 02:00:36.840
[Guest]: body you're not going to even know this and even though I've written a book

02:00:36.840 --> 02:00:40.760
[Guest]: about this it's a constant struggle you know sometimes even before I sit down to

02:00:40.760 --> 02:00:44.280
[Guest]: eat I think what am I going to watch with this today you know because my

02:00:44.280 --> 02:00:47.720
[Guest]: eating time is sometimes my only free time in the day and I have other

02:00:47.720 --> 02:00:51.600
[Guest]: deadlines lined up and things to do so I feel this is the only time I can give

02:00:51.600 --> 02:00:55.520
[Guest]: myself a break and watch something but why don't I treat the food itself as a

02:00:55.520 --> 02:01:00.840
[Guest]: break why do I need an additional crutch to add on to this break right and this

02:01:00.840 --> 02:01:04.920
[Guest]: is interesting thing last December November I started watching these Korean

02:01:04.920 --> 02:01:09.840
[Guest]: YouTube vloggers I'm not talking about Kdrama I haven't started watching that

02:01:09.840 --> 02:01:14.160
[Guest]: yet despite too much pressure on Twitter I see that everywhere you know I was

02:01:14.160 --> 02:01:18.680
[Guest]: fascinated by the way they lead their lives and these are not just Koreans in

02:01:18.680 --> 02:01:23.520
[Guest]: Korea but also the ones who live in US and other places and trust me it was

02:01:23.520 --> 02:01:27.920
[Guest]: like a rabbit hole and I could never come out of it it was so fascinating and

02:01:27.920 --> 02:01:33.320
[Guest]: riveting how slow how meaningful how mindful they lead their life and I'm not

02:01:33.320 --> 02:01:37.080
[Guest]: saying because somebody on YouTube just posted a vlog about that and that's how

02:01:37.080 --> 02:01:41.560
[Guest]: they all are but it does give me the impression that they definitely stick to

02:01:41.560 --> 02:01:44.880
[Guest]: these traditions they take this very seriously they believe in cooking

02:01:44.880 --> 02:01:49.960
[Guest]: everything from scratch and even their children and the next generation loves

02:01:49.960 --> 02:01:54.200
[Guest]: Korean traditional food and no matter because their food also has quite

02:01:54.200 --> 02:01:57.920
[Guest]: different kinds of sometimes bitter they even use things like karela in their

02:01:57.920 --> 02:02:01.680
[Guest]: cooking and you know the kids eat everything and they all sit together at

02:02:01.680 --> 02:02:06.080
[Guest]: the table and this is one scene which I won't forget there's this and they also

02:02:06.080 --> 02:02:08.960
[Guest]: show a lot of cleaning in their videos they're obsessed with keeping their

02:02:08.960 --> 02:02:13.000
[Guest]: house spotlessly clean and I watched that while saying that my own room is

02:02:13.000 --> 02:02:18.360
[Guest]: dirty but I'm watching that and you know after cleaning the bathroom and

02:02:18.360 --> 02:02:22.160
[Guest]: everything scrubbing the whole house clean she'll come to her balcony and

02:02:22.160 --> 02:02:28.080
[Guest]: make herself a like a small pot of some beautiful tea and in a small plate some

02:02:28.080 --> 02:02:34.400
[Guest]: two pieces of cake and cookie and she'll keep it on her table on the balcony no

02:02:34.400 --> 02:02:39.360
[Guest]: no gadgets no books nothing around and she will slowly be sipping that and

02:02:39.360 --> 02:02:44.360
[Guest]: eating that while one cat is purring around so this is the classic scene and

02:02:44.360 --> 02:02:49.520
[Guest]: it made me feel like I want that life and I want to be in that mental state

02:02:49.520 --> 02:02:53.720
[Guest]: where you know I finish all the housework and I take this break with a

02:02:53.720 --> 02:02:58.840
[Guest]: cup of tea and a cake which I eat and drink absolutely guilt-free and I feel

02:02:58.840 --> 02:03:03.640
[Guest]: like I have earned this and putting my whole mind and all my five senses into

02:03:03.640 --> 02:03:08.800
[Guest]: this experience and how can that cake make you gain weight because it has

02:03:08.800 --> 02:03:14.560
[Guest]: already released so much of happy hormones the good kind of hormones instead of the

02:03:14.560 --> 02:03:18.280
[Guest]: stressful cortisol that actually makes you accumulate the belly fat and all

02:03:18.280 --> 02:03:23.600
[Guest]: that so I feel like this is why how you eat is so important imagine just going

02:03:23.600 --> 02:03:27.520
[Guest]: through a drive-thru like in a country where there's a drive-thru and buying

02:03:27.520 --> 02:03:31.400
[Guest]: some of these you know cakes or some milkshakes or something and drinking in

02:03:31.400 --> 02:03:35.520
[Guest]: the car and going away that is so American but you know when you see this

02:03:35.520 --> 02:03:40.440
[Guest]: stark difference in Korea and their culture you know there's so much to

02:03:40.440 --> 02:03:43.960
[Guest]: learn from that I'm sure Indians were also like that but these guys just make

02:03:43.960 --> 02:03:48.920
[Guest]: the most aesthetic and pleasing videos that make you aspire to that kind of

02:03:48.920 --> 02:03:53.440
[Amit Varma]: life. In fact this is another cinematic moment like I can think of you know if a

02:03:53.440 --> 02:03:57.800
[Amit Varma]: film of your life would begin with you know Eli Roth or Louis Bunuel perhaps

02:03:57.800 --> 02:04:01.640
[Amit Varma]: directing that scene where the skull is being cut open and they're singing

02:04:01.640 --> 02:04:05.440
[Amit Varma]: happy birthday it could end with you know Ozu directing the last scene of the

02:04:05.440 --> 02:04:09.600
[Amit Varma]: closing credits where you're in the balcony with a little cup of tea and one

02:04:09.600 --> 02:04:14.600
[Amit Varma]: little biscuit and there's just peace and quiet and focus so suddenly you know

02:04:14.600 --> 02:04:18.240
[Amit Varma]: a full journey we have kind of traveled here those who of course were Japanese

02:04:18.240 --> 02:04:24.320
[Amit Varma]: and not Korean but you know similar feels as it were. The other aspect of

02:04:24.320 --> 02:04:28.360
[Amit Varma]: you know what you describe about your great-grandparents table is

02:04:28.360 --> 02:04:34.400
[Amit Varma]: something that almost seems to me to become a virtue out of necessity like

02:04:34.400 --> 02:04:39.760
[Amit Varma]: you point out that they eat food which is local seasonal cheap they don't cook

02:04:39.760 --> 02:04:43.080
[Amit Varma]: more than they are going to eat at a particular meal but that flows from

02:04:43.080 --> 02:04:47.040
[Amit Varma]: necessity because there are no fridges so they can't store food there are no

02:04:47.040 --> 02:04:49.960
[Amit Varma]: fridges the world is not so interconnected that food can come from

02:04:49.960 --> 02:04:54.680
[Amit Varma]: wherever so out of necessity you are eating local seasonal and cheap and that

02:04:54.680 --> 02:04:58.840
[Amit Varma]: becomes a virtue. Now you know going back to what Pauline said and of course

02:04:58.840 --> 02:05:01.600
[Amit Varma]: Pauline didn't literally mean that you have to eat what your great great great

02:05:01.600 --> 02:05:06.640
[Amit Varma]: great grandmother ate. Two conflicting thoughts come up here for me and one

02:05:06.640 --> 02:05:09.960
[Amit Varma]: thought of course is the classic conservative thought that if there is a

02:05:09.960 --> 02:05:14.120
[Amit Varma]: particular diet that has evolved over a period of time if your grandmother said

02:05:14.120 --> 02:05:17.760
[Amit Varma]: this is healthy eat this there's a reason it has evolved because it works

02:05:17.760 --> 02:05:23.040
[Amit Varma]: for you and sometimes our traditions have sort of deeper reasonings behind

02:05:23.040 --> 02:05:27.000
[Amit Varma]: them which might not necessarily be a reasoning that was scientific to begin

02:05:27.000 --> 02:05:31.200
[Amit Varma]: with but just comes from the practice through generations and so on and there

02:05:31.200 --> 02:05:35.720
[Amit Varma]: is much value and merit in that. At the same time it strikes me that our great

02:05:35.720 --> 02:05:39.640
[Amit Varma]: great grandparents didn't have access to either a lot of the food or the

02:05:39.640 --> 02:05:43.360
[Amit Varma]: knowledge that we do like we are surrounded by so many different kinds of

02:05:43.360 --> 02:05:48.800
[Amit Varma]: foods today that our grandparents would not have known and and the question then

02:05:48.800 --> 02:05:54.760
[Amit Varma]: comes up is that you know how how does one evolve a set of values around what

02:05:54.760 --> 02:05:59.800
[Amit Varma]: one is to eat like when you think of your own eating for example so there is

02:05:59.800 --> 02:06:02.960
[Amit Varma]: a certain kind of food that you like eating that because you've grown up

02:06:02.960 --> 02:06:07.280
[Amit Varma]: eating that and you acquire tastes along the way but at some point in time you've

02:06:07.280 --> 02:06:11.000
[Amit Varma]: clearly thought and said that this is the kind of food that I want to eat and

02:06:11.000 --> 02:06:14.880
[Amit Varma]: this is my philosophy behind this kind of food this is why I want to eat this

02:06:14.880 --> 02:06:18.680
[Amit Varma]: kind of food and at the same time of course I do want it to be tasty as well

02:06:18.680 --> 02:06:24.040
[Amit Varma]: so it is not only you know this thing. How did you evolve your way of thinking

02:06:24.040 --> 02:06:29.120
[Amit Varma]: about food and where would you say it has kind of arrived today. I've been a

02:06:29.120 --> 02:06:35.120
[Guest]: vegetarian since I was born I was born in a vegetarian family and of course I

02:06:35.120 --> 02:06:43.120
[Guest]: ate eggs and that was the limit of my you know dietary habits. See currently

02:06:43.120 --> 02:06:47.200
[Guest]: like you said I'm always grown up eating Tamil food South Indian food there was

02:06:47.200 --> 02:06:53.040
[Guest]: not like much experimentation happening my one of my aunts was like keen on

02:06:53.040 --> 02:06:57.680
[Guest]: trying out new things and she would like cut things from magazines and try them

02:06:57.680 --> 02:07:02.920
[Guest]: out and I was like a willing taster for everything so that exposed me a little

02:07:02.920 --> 02:07:09.400
[Guest]: bit outside of our very traditional food but growing up that was it and you know

02:07:09.400 --> 02:07:13.800
[Guest]: we were not like the very restaurant visiting family either because one very

02:07:13.800 --> 02:07:19.480
[Guest]: middle-class and money had to be saved for more important things and also you

02:07:19.480 --> 02:07:23.640
[Guest]: know we had like a couple of restaurants in the Dadar, Sayan area where we would

02:07:23.640 --> 02:07:28.800
[Guest]: love the food and we'd go like once in few months as a treat and I just would

02:07:28.800 --> 02:07:35.240
[Guest]: order the same thing you know in these places and that was my food world and

02:07:35.240 --> 02:07:39.080
[Guest]: it's not like we had like too much of a social circle of friends or eating at

02:07:39.080 --> 02:07:43.880
[Guest]: other people's houses so I was not even exposed much to other Indian cuisines

02:07:43.880 --> 02:07:50.560
[Guest]: let alone much of foreign cuisines but today as you say there's been such an

02:07:50.560 --> 02:07:56.320
[Guest]: explosion in the last decade or so from things like food shows, cookbooks,

02:07:56.320 --> 02:08:04.680
[Guest]: magazines, YouTube and you know on the web so much of content and even stuff

02:08:04.680 --> 02:08:09.880
[Guest]: that's available like at the click of a button on Amazon you can order anything

02:08:09.880 --> 02:08:14.600
[Guest]: right from gochugaru to a smoked paprika to you name it you will get it

02:08:14.600 --> 02:08:20.120
[Guest]: instantly so availability is there all the kind of creative ideas are there and

02:08:20.120 --> 02:08:24.280
[Guest]: if you are interested in trying out these new things and of course there's

02:08:24.280 --> 02:08:29.720
[Guest]: whole bunch of restaurants and delivery services so it is so much stimulation

02:08:29.720 --> 02:08:34.540
[Guest]: available for you to choose from so it becomes increasingly difficult what the

02:08:34.540 --> 02:08:39.000
[Guest]: hell do I eat you know sometimes you know I tell my husband I'm not going to

02:08:39.000 --> 02:08:43.520
[Guest]: cook today I'm very bored and you say okay let's order and then we figure out

02:08:43.520 --> 02:08:46.360
[Guest]: for half an hour, one hour what to order and I said I would have just finished

02:08:46.360 --> 02:08:51.120
[Guest]: cooking in this much time you know so it's just like what to order and what to

02:08:51.120 --> 02:08:54.720
[Guest]: eat is like you just tear your hair over that and it's sometimes more painful

02:08:54.720 --> 02:08:59.240
[Guest]: than the cooking process itself so how do you even choose what to cook and

02:08:59.240 --> 02:09:04.320
[Guest]: sometimes sometimes I go about the way of a menu plan where I tell myself also

02:09:04.320 --> 02:09:08.520
[Guest]: in some sometimes I'm in the middle of some recipe testing for my books or my

02:09:08.520 --> 02:09:13.160
[Guest]: column etc so I will write down that I want to make these things in the week

02:09:13.160 --> 02:09:17.960
[Guest]: and sometimes something catches my fancy online and I say okay I wish I could try

02:09:17.960 --> 02:09:23.200
[Guest]: that out and I will make a note of that but then you know some I just go back to

02:09:23.200 --> 02:09:29.040
[Guest]: sambar rice and sabzi because I don't want to think about what to make and I

02:09:29.040 --> 02:09:34.080
[Guest]: don't have to you know read my whole kitchen which ingredient is where this

02:09:34.080 --> 02:09:39.120
[Guest]: that and just keep it very simple and I think five days a week I just keep it

02:09:39.120 --> 02:09:43.460
[Guest]: very very simple because I think like Steve Jobs who just knew what to wear in

02:09:43.460 --> 02:09:47.160
[Guest]: the morning every day I just feel more comfortable knowing what am I going to

02:09:47.160 --> 02:09:52.400
[Guest]: cook every day I don't want to be raking my head in the morning what's for lunch

02:09:52.400 --> 02:09:58.480
[Guest]: what's for dinner so I think one is a comfort of going back to tradition and

02:09:58.480 --> 02:10:04.720
[Guest]: two not having the hassle of thinking too much about what so within the

02:10:04.720 --> 02:10:10.760
[Guest]: spectrum how can I eat healthy maybe one day I will eat millets and I'll have

02:10:10.760 --> 02:10:15.480
[Guest]: some kind of raw salad along with my meal and I in the vegetable it will be

02:10:15.480 --> 02:10:20.080
[Guest]: something seasonal and you know am I having something fermented like dahi or

02:10:20.080 --> 02:10:25.200
[Guest]: some pickle with this so within the construct of my traditional food I just

02:10:25.200 --> 02:10:30.760
[Guest]: figure out what is available what is the best see also even cooking is a process

02:10:30.760 --> 02:10:34.920
[Guest]: of choosing from the best ingredients and making something nice out of it and

02:10:34.920 --> 02:10:39.200
[Guest]: in this case by best I mean what is the healthiest and best for you for your

02:10:39.200 --> 02:10:43.480
[Guest]: health and if I could choose from ten different things okay I want to put this

02:10:43.480 --> 02:10:47.000
[Guest]: this this together in my plate today but I know what I'm going to make if it's

02:10:47.000 --> 02:10:51.000
[Guest]: just like a sambar or a rasam or a curry I just know have to apply that into this

02:10:51.000 --> 02:10:55.760
[Guest]: that process just makes it simpler when you are the one cooking because I have

02:10:55.760 --> 02:11:00.040
[Guest]: seen friends and people who you know they are outside and their cook calls

02:11:00.040 --> 02:11:05.280
[Guest]: them from out ki madam kya banao and they just say kuch bhi banao because they

02:11:05.280 --> 02:11:09.580
[Guest]: one they've outsourced the whole cooking process outsource the buying of the

02:11:09.580 --> 02:11:13.040
[Guest]: grocery and stuff now you're also outsourcing the process of deciding what

02:11:13.040 --> 02:11:16.920
[Guest]: you are going to eat the person who's cooking for you I find that most

02:11:16.920 --> 02:11:21.240
[Guest]: fascinating amusing and also like boss why are you giving away your health in

02:11:21.240 --> 02:11:25.120
[Guest]: your cooks hands like you can't even decide what you want to eat you know

02:11:25.120 --> 02:11:31.840
[Guest]: because even that process is so tough telling the cook what to cook no it's

02:11:31.840 --> 02:11:35.600
[Amit Varma]: it's all fascinating and you mentioned Steve Jobs and obviously the reason

02:11:35.600 --> 02:11:39.240
[Amit Varma]: Jobs used to kind of wear the same clothes every day like not literally the

02:11:39.240 --> 02:11:42.600
[Amit Varma]: same clothes clothes but you know that the same kind of uniform as it were the

02:11:42.600 --> 02:11:46.000
[Amit Varma]: black turtleneck shirt and the jeans was to avoid what cognitive psychologists

02:11:46.000 --> 02:11:49.840
[Amit Varma]: call decision fatigue because every decision you take through a day tires

02:11:49.840 --> 02:11:53.800
[Amit Varma]: you out and you want to save as much energy as possible and one way of jobs

02:11:53.800 --> 02:11:56.920
[Amit Varma]: was that he doesn't have to decide what he's going to wear so it's the same

02:11:56.920 --> 02:12:00.960
[Amit Varma]: thing every day and equally in your first book which is the everyday healthy

02:12:00.960 --> 02:12:05.220
[Amit Varma]: vegetarian which you wrote in 2017 for Hachette you spoke about I think the

02:12:05.220 --> 02:12:08.440
[Amit Varma]: importance of menu preparation of deciding in advance what you're going to

02:12:08.440 --> 02:12:12.240
[Amit Varma]: eat through the week and all of that and that kind of brings me to my next

02:12:12.240 --> 02:12:17.040
[Amit Varma]: question now one reason for doing that would obviously be to save yourself from

02:12:17.040 --> 02:12:20.080
[Amit Varma]: decision fatigue so rather than tire yourself out by thinking what you're

02:12:20.080 --> 02:12:23.320
[Amit Varma]: going to eat you can decide a menu for the week in advance and just go with

02:12:23.320 --> 02:12:26.660
[Amit Varma]: that but the other aspect of that is that what you're really doing there it

02:12:26.660 --> 02:12:30.760
[Amit Varma]: seems to me is setting out a process for yourself like one of my favorite self

02:12:30.760 --> 02:12:34.880
[Amit Varma]: help books of modern times is James Clear's atomic habits where he talks

02:12:34.880 --> 02:12:39.240
[Amit Varma]: about how it's more important to have processes and goals that everybody can

02:12:39.240 --> 02:12:42.840
[Amit Varma]: have great goals but the only people who achieve those goals are the people who

02:12:42.840 --> 02:12:47.600
[Amit Varma]: have great processes and it strikes me that you know when one is eating it's

02:12:47.600 --> 02:12:52.360
[Amit Varma]: you know more important to just build healthy eating habits over a time

02:12:52.360 --> 02:12:56.840
[Amit Varma]: through certain processes rather than set yourself a target like you know I

02:12:56.840 --> 02:13:02.040
[Amit Varma]: will eat so many calories every day or I will lose so much weight by this period

02:13:02.040 --> 02:13:05.360
[Amit Varma]: of time and all of that and those goals can get counterproductive and the goals

02:13:05.360 --> 02:13:09.440
[Amit Varma]: alone can stress you out whereas if you just internalize a self-image of

02:13:09.440 --> 02:13:12.600
[Amit Varma]: yourself like I am a person who eats healthy I am a person who eats at

02:13:12.600 --> 02:13:15.000
[Amit Varma]: particular times and that's another thing you mentioned about your

02:13:15.000 --> 02:13:20.240
[Amit Varma]: grandparents that they ate at these fixed particular times during the day so

02:13:20.240 --> 02:13:24.800
[Amit Varma]: like one I guess it's a two-step process one you build a prism through which you

02:13:24.800 --> 02:13:28.080
[Amit Varma]: look at food which you built in which you've kind of outlined in your book as

02:13:28.080 --> 02:13:31.880
[Amit Varma]: well and we'll talk a little more about that now but and then once you build that

02:13:31.880 --> 02:13:37.640
[Amit Varma]: prism you use it to build processes and then everything takes care of itself is

02:13:37.640 --> 02:13:42.240
[Amit Varma]: that an accurate description is that how you've sort of approached it yeah you're

02:13:42.240 --> 02:13:47.440
[Guest]: right because see healthy eating more than anything else it is the planning

02:13:47.440 --> 02:13:52.480
[Guest]: that counts because I may have all the good intentions but when I open my fridge

02:13:52.480 --> 02:13:57.520
[Guest]: and the first thing I see is like a desert in front of me and if I'm hungry

02:13:57.520 --> 02:14:01.860
[Guest]: I am going to reach out for that I mean it's it's not willpower or anything it's

02:14:01.860 --> 02:14:06.080
[Guest]: just that it's there so what you see is what you eat if I had planned a little

02:14:06.080 --> 02:14:11.000
[Guest]: bit better and if I had kept things like a hummus or some vegetables or some you

02:14:11.000 --> 02:14:15.520
[Guest]: know fruits which are cut and ready in transparent containers when I open the

02:14:15.520 --> 02:14:21.120
[Guest]: fridge that is what I see so that is the planning that you know telling yourself

02:14:21.120 --> 02:14:26.340
[Guest]: what are you going to eat like even when they tell people to visualize your

02:14:26.340 --> 02:14:31.400
[Guest]: success right like you imagine yourself going and doing all that so this kind of

02:14:31.400 --> 02:14:34.880
[Guest]: planning is that I'm only telling myself tomorrow I'm going to eat this this this

02:14:34.880 --> 02:14:39.960
[Guest]: and you know if we have told ourselves that that plan is already in place so

02:14:39.960 --> 02:14:43.860
[Guest]: when I get hungry I don't have to think about what am I going to eat now because

02:14:43.860 --> 02:14:47.960
[Guest]: when you're hungry most likely the decision you take will not be a correct

02:14:47.960 --> 02:14:52.600
[Guest]: decision anyway so for those times is when which is why they also say that you

02:14:52.600 --> 02:14:56.120
[Guest]: never go for food shopping when you're hungry always go after you've had your

02:14:56.120 --> 02:15:01.560
[Guest]: lunch and because that definitely impacts the way you think and the choices

02:15:01.560 --> 02:15:07.040
[Guest]: you make so having a plan in place is the first step towards any kind of

02:15:07.040 --> 02:15:10.600
[Guest]: healthy eating even if you're going to order out you tell yourself that these

02:15:10.600 --> 02:15:14.880
[Guest]: are the restaurants this these are the dishes and keep a list of them and you

02:15:14.880 --> 02:15:19.240
[Guest]: know that of all the other choices these may be better so I'm going to order from

02:15:19.240 --> 02:15:24.440
[Guest]: these so and that's how you can even be prepared stock up for these things and

02:15:24.440 --> 02:15:29.440
[Guest]: have all the things you need for a certain meal or something already

02:15:29.440 --> 02:15:33.240
[Guest]: because then it's so tough if you want you have the intention you want to eat

02:15:33.240 --> 02:15:36.560
[Guest]: something healthy but there is nothing available and when you open your fridge

02:15:36.560 --> 02:15:40.880
[Guest]: the only things that you see are things that are not good for you then how is it

02:15:40.880 --> 02:15:45.920
[Guest]: going to help you stick to your plan it's going to be so difficult so I try

02:15:45.920 --> 02:15:49.840
[Guest]: to follow that and of course all this planning and prepping it does take so

02:15:49.840 --> 02:15:54.720
[Guest]: much time and effort and it is tough I'm not saying no but if you keep doing this

02:15:54.720 --> 02:15:58.320
[Guest]: it kind of becomes a second habit like when you order your groceries you also

02:15:58.320 --> 02:16:04.240
[Guest]: order a few couple of fruits or you know something like that so yeah so that

02:16:04.240 --> 02:16:09.720
[Guest]: that's that's a simple way to go about this the planning and processes and

02:16:09.720 --> 02:16:14.280
[Amit Varma]: being well prepared no and I guess there are ways to even outsource little bits

02:16:14.280 --> 02:16:17.440
[Amit Varma]: of that like when I was in Quito I realized that there are these services

02:16:17.440 --> 02:16:21.600
[Unknown]: in you know Mumbai and I'm sure even Bangalore who'll provide you four keto

02:16:21.600 --> 02:16:24.720
[Amit Varma]: meals a day so you don't actually even have to think about it or there are apps

02:16:24.720 --> 02:16:29.600
[Amit Varma]: where which will calculate the calories of everything and tell you what you

02:16:29.600 --> 02:16:34.040
[Amit Varma]: should have next to meet your macros and all of that my next question is kind of

02:16:34.040 --> 02:16:37.600
[Amit Varma]: about a theme that I've thought a bit about but I've only sort of while

02:16:37.600 --> 02:16:41.320
[Amit Varma]: chatting with you it struck me that it applies to food as well which is about

02:16:41.320 --> 02:16:45.760
[Amit Varma]: how you know along with the great technological advances we have had in

02:16:45.760 --> 02:16:48.760
[Amit Varma]: these times all of which are a blessing to us and have made our lives so much

02:16:48.760 --> 02:16:53.000
[Amit Varma]: better and which in fact are enabling this conversation there are also some

02:16:53.000 --> 02:16:57.320
[Amit Varma]: that have a flip side and the flip side is that there is a lot of technology

02:16:57.320 --> 02:17:01.480
[Amit Varma]: today for manipulation of the brain for example in the context of social media

02:17:01.480 --> 02:17:06.360
[Amit Varma]: everything becomes much more addictive that people have sort of figured out and

02:17:06.360 --> 02:17:10.440
[Amit Varma]: in my years as a professional gambler I kind of read up a lot on how casinos do

02:17:10.440 --> 02:17:15.240
[Amit Varma]: this also how the lights and the sounds and all of that will ensure that you

02:17:15.240 --> 02:17:19.960
[Amit Varma]: keep chasing the next dopamine rush and similarly you know social media also

02:17:19.960 --> 02:17:24.960
[Amit Varma]: does that it's meant to keep keep you on that dopamine like you know one of the

02:17:24.960 --> 02:17:28.320
[Amit Varma]: things that some of the apps did a few years ago I think they all probably do

02:17:28.320 --> 02:17:31.640
[Amit Varma]: it now is that if you press the back button you wouldn't go back the screen

02:17:31.640 --> 02:17:35.600
[Amit Varma]: would refresh so you'd have more stories so you simply can't get away you're

02:17:35.600 --> 02:17:39.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of trapped and it strikes me that this also happens in the context of food

02:17:39.360 --> 02:17:43.400
[Amit Varma]: where our brain is drawn towards sweet food there are certain kind of foods

02:17:43.400 --> 02:17:47.360
[Amit Varma]: that we get addicted to like I really think that carbs in a sense are an

02:17:47.360 --> 02:17:52.000
[Amit Varma]: addiction this is an addiction that processed foods take advantage of they

02:17:52.000 --> 02:17:56.320
[Amit Varma]: are not just designed to be tasty or and they're not just designed to have some

02:17:56.320 --> 02:17:59.960
[Amit Varma]: nutrition as and when they do but they are designed to be addictive in fact

02:17:59.960 --> 02:18:04.160
[Amit Varma]: that is a fundamental you know design imperative of processed food because

02:18:04.160 --> 02:18:07.840
[Amit Varma]: whoever's making them wants you to go out and buy them again and again and

02:18:07.840 --> 02:18:11.640
[Amit Varma]: again and this also makes them incredibly unhealthy and this is

02:18:11.640 --> 02:18:16.160
[Amit Varma]: something that you've also you know spoken about in your book so tell me a

02:18:16.160 --> 02:18:20.760
[Amit Varma]: little bit about processed foods and what can we do to fight them because a

02:18:20.760 --> 02:18:24.480
[Amit Varma]: lot of processed foods are common everyday foods like white sugar or

02:18:24.480 --> 02:18:28.000
[Amit Varma]: tomato ketchup you know how should we reduce the kind of processed foods we

02:18:28.000 --> 02:18:32.920
[Amit Varma]: take are there any processed foods which are actually okay and you know what is

02:18:32.920 --> 02:18:37.880
[Guest]: your approach to all of this see the processed food industry I'm sure they

02:18:37.880 --> 02:18:45.640
[Guest]: spend millions or billions of dollars on just the science of creating an

02:18:45.640 --> 02:18:51.680
[Guest]: addictive combination in matters of flavor so people just it's like that you

02:18:51.680 --> 02:18:56.640
[Guest]: can't eat just one tagline of Lay's right and that's how they are designed

02:18:56.640 --> 02:19:03.120
[Guest]: to be and recently I was reading up on this thing about comfort foods right the

02:19:03.120 --> 02:19:06.760
[Guest]: kind of foods that we reach out to when we are feeling low and we want to feel

02:19:06.760 --> 02:19:12.960
[Guest]: better etc and invariably a comfort food anywhere in the world will be a

02:19:12.960 --> 02:19:21.320
[Guest]: combination of sugar fat and carbs in some way and either one or two or all

02:19:21.320 --> 02:19:26.800
[Guest]: three of these it goes back to when we were babies you know when we were

02:19:26.800 --> 02:19:30.840
[Guest]: agitated or when we would cry when we would be hungry mothers would feed us

02:19:30.840 --> 02:19:36.960
[Guest]: breast milk or any milk bottled milk and that milk had the same combination of

02:19:36.960 --> 02:19:42.520
[Guest]: sugars fats and carbs that would instantly soothe us and babies either go

02:19:42.520 --> 02:19:49.040
[Guest]: to sleep or they stop crying right so that same thing has continued as a part

02:19:49.040 --> 02:19:53.680
[Guest]: of our evolution all into our adulthood there that same combination of food no

02:19:53.680 --> 02:19:58.440
[Guest]: matter what the end result may not be milk at all it may be chips or it may be

02:19:58.440 --> 02:20:04.480
[Guest]: a desert or it may be pasta or whatever it is that same combination of compounds

02:20:04.480 --> 02:20:10.080
[Guest]: triggers off that same dopamine kind of scenario in our brain where we feel

02:20:10.080 --> 02:20:14.840
[Guest]: soothed and comforted and the way we would feel as babies so it is something

02:20:14.840 --> 02:20:20.720
[Guest]: as basic as that and no matter what diet somebody's on they cannot be not

02:20:20.720 --> 02:20:25.880
[Guest]: comforted with these kind of foods and that's why it becomes all the more a big

02:20:25.880 --> 02:20:31.840
[Guest]: struggle to you know avoid these things in my life I mean not anyone's life and

02:20:31.840 --> 02:20:36.480
[Guest]: you know I often tell people that if I have to give up rice then I might as

02:20:36.480 --> 02:20:40.040
[Guest]: well give up living because what am I going to do with my life if you tell me

02:20:40.040 --> 02:20:46.440
[Guest]: I can't eat rice ever so I think this this is definitely one aspect of it and

02:20:46.440 --> 02:20:51.560
[Guest]: the processed food industry takes maximum advantage of the fact that these

02:20:51.560 --> 02:20:56.280
[Guest]: three compounds you given any combination plus with the added flavor

02:20:56.280 --> 02:21:01.640
[Guest]: molecules which they have done so much worth of research on they know that

02:21:01.640 --> 02:21:06.200
[Guest]: people are going to be hooked to this product and in my book I have written

02:21:06.200 --> 02:21:11.160
[Guest]: about the very basic cornflakes or the cereal that a lot of Indians have moved

02:21:11.160 --> 02:21:14.840
[Guest]: towards eating that for breakfast because you just remove it from a box

02:21:14.840 --> 02:21:19.920
[Guest]: and you add some milk and you add some fruit and you think it's healthy but

02:21:19.920 --> 02:21:26.440
[Guest]: compare a cornflakes to a Bhutta or the full the corn on the cob that we see in

02:21:26.440 --> 02:21:31.040
[Guest]: the monsoons and now pretty much see around the year so that is the real food

02:21:31.040 --> 02:21:35.840
[Guest]: at least close to real because even that must have gone through some chemical

02:21:35.840 --> 02:21:42.400
[Guest]: processes and whatever but each of those corn kernels the ectosperm or the skin

02:21:42.400 --> 02:21:49.480
[Guest]: is peeled off then it is cooked then it is dried and then it is roasted and then

02:21:49.480 --> 02:21:53.800
[Guest]: it is a flattened and then it is packaged and in the middle of these

02:21:53.800 --> 02:21:59.000
[Guest]: processes you get all the additives of sugar salt flavorings all the artificial

02:21:59.000 --> 02:22:04.200
[Guest]: strawberry fruit flavor or the chocolate flavor and of course preservatives so

02:22:04.200 --> 02:22:07.880
[Guest]: that you can buy it and keep it even for one year nothing will go wrong try to

02:22:07.880 --> 02:22:11.880
[Guest]: keep like a corn on the cob for one year in your fridge and see what happens

02:22:11.880 --> 02:22:17.080
[Guest]: right so we don't even realize we think how I ate cornflakes this is called a

02:22:17.080 --> 02:22:22.240
[Guest]: healthy brand of cornflakes and I've had it with milk and fruit and honey all of

02:22:22.240 --> 02:22:26.200
[Guest]: it is very healthy so we feel happy that we've eaten something healthy but if we

02:22:26.200 --> 02:22:31.280
[Guest]: give a little thought as to what process has gone behind you know from its

02:22:31.280 --> 02:22:35.680
[Guest]: natural form to the form that you see it in front of you what are all the

02:22:35.680 --> 02:22:40.160
[Guest]: processes that have gone into it and it could all have been avoided if you chose

02:22:40.160 --> 02:22:44.760
[Guest]: something as simple as a poha which is just rice which has been flattened so

02:22:44.760 --> 02:22:48.720
[Guest]: the number of processes have been so less and then you make it in whatever

02:22:48.720 --> 02:22:53.760
[Guest]: way you want right so even like in the Bengalis they just have that with milk

02:22:53.760 --> 02:22:59.520
[Guest]: the poha right and some sugar so even that is much less process than eating

02:22:59.520 --> 02:23:05.720
[Guest]: your processed cereal so I think the first step is definitely awareness and

02:23:05.720 --> 02:23:09.880
[Guest]: again that question of mindfulness comes in because if I'm in a hurry I'm just

02:23:09.880 --> 02:23:15.320
[Guest]: shaking that box of cereal into my bowl and adding milk and eating it on the go

02:23:15.320 --> 02:23:19.560
[Guest]: where am I going to spend a minute thinking about what how did this

02:23:19.560 --> 02:23:24.440
[Guest]: cornflakes come across and how did it become like this what is there in it

02:23:24.440 --> 02:23:28.880
[Guest]: have I read the nutritional label do I know what ingredients these are do they

02:23:28.880 --> 02:23:33.480
[Guest]: even sound like food so you know and like I said initially it may be a bit

02:23:33.480 --> 02:23:37.720
[Guest]: tiresome because we are surrounded by things like this and I don't say it is

02:23:37.720 --> 02:23:41.800
[Guest]: easy at all to think about everything that we put in our mouth then we say I'd

02:23:41.800 --> 02:23:46.360
[Guest]: rather be fasting because this is too complicated but I think having this

02:23:46.360 --> 02:23:51.520
[Guest]: basic knowledge about at least the 10-15 things that you eat on a regular basis

02:23:51.520 --> 02:23:56.160
[Guest]: and translating that knowledge into a second nature by which you just know

02:23:56.160 --> 02:24:01.920
[Guest]: what is good you don't and I think human beings as a race we have been innately

02:24:01.920 --> 02:24:06.800
[Guest]: using food as medicine we know what is good for us in the hunter-gatherer thing

02:24:06.800 --> 02:24:10.960
[Guest]: they didn't have any barcode or app to tell them what is this how many calories

02:24:10.960 --> 02:24:17.400
[Guest]: is this and stuff they just knew and I think over the last thousands of years

02:24:17.400 --> 02:24:22.520
[Guest]: we have moved away so much from our inherent knowledge and trusting our own

02:24:22.520 --> 02:24:27.280
[Guest]: instincts that for everything we have to either Google or understand what is

02:24:27.280 --> 02:24:33.280
[Guest]: happening so I think as humans we have lost the we have lost the knowledge or

02:24:33.280 --> 02:24:37.200
[Guest]: that inherent knowledge of what foods are good for us what we should go for

02:24:37.200 --> 02:24:42.680
[Guest]: and I think we have distanced ourselves so much and a lot of industries lobbies

02:24:42.680 --> 02:24:46.760
[Guest]: and all they are also responsible for that but we are also responsible in a

02:24:46.760 --> 02:24:50.720
[Guest]: way that we have not been so careful we just think okay it's something I'm going

02:24:50.720 --> 02:24:53.280
[Guest]: to eat it you don't realize that there is something external which you're

02:24:53.280 --> 02:24:57.920
[Guest]: putting into your body which is going to become part of your body in the next 24

02:24:57.920 --> 02:25:03.920
[Guest]: hours and you don't give it that much importance so I think understanding food

02:25:03.920 --> 02:25:09.000
[Guest]: is more important than just trusting these YouTube videos or these Instagram

02:25:09.000 --> 02:25:13.080
[Guest]: posts with millions of views where they just say this is good this is bad very

02:25:13.080 --> 02:25:19.200
[Guest]: binary very yes and no kind of answers which is very easy for people because it

02:25:19.200 --> 02:25:24.280
[Guest]: saves their time and their effort but do these people even know your body do they

02:25:24.280 --> 02:25:29.200
[Guest]: know your lifestyle your culture because it is it is never a yes and no it's

02:25:29.200 --> 02:25:35.640
[Guest]: never a binary it is so complicated and it is so personalized and it differs

02:25:35.640 --> 02:25:39.640
[Guest]: from person to person so how can you just believe something that gives you

02:25:39.640 --> 02:25:44.480
[Guest]: such an oversimplified information just because you don't want to spend time and

02:25:44.480 --> 02:25:48.160
[Guest]: invest that time into your own health by understanding what you should eat

02:25:48.160 --> 02:25:51.440
[Guest]: because you are the only person who knows what is best for you yeah and it

02:25:51.440 --> 02:25:54.560
[Amit Varma]: strikes me that you know earlier we spoke of decision fatigue and Steve

02:25:54.560 --> 02:25:57.640
[Amit Varma]: Jobs and all of that and one of the ways people deal with decision fatigue is

02:25:57.640 --> 02:26:01.640
[Amit Varma]: something called satisficing which is a combination of satisfying and sufficing

02:26:01.640 --> 02:26:06.040
[Amit Varma]: where you're satisfied with something that suffices and a lot of people do

02:26:06.040 --> 02:26:10.520
[Amit Varma]: satisficing when it comes to their diet and that makes no sense because it's a

02:26:10.520 --> 02:26:13.840
[Amit Varma]: question of what you're putting inside your own body it is shaping the

02:26:13.840 --> 02:26:17.240
[Amit Varma]: well-being of your future self why on earth would you want to satisfy with

02:26:17.240 --> 02:26:20.440
[Amit Varma]: that you can satisfy say if you're going out to buy a new shirt or a toaster or

02:26:20.440 --> 02:26:24.160
[Amit Varma]: whatever but when it comes to the food that you're putting inside your own body

02:26:24.160 --> 02:26:27.720
[Amit Varma]: you you should not be absent-minded you should not go with the flow or you

02:26:27.720 --> 02:26:32.000
[Amit Varma]: should not follow like you said what an influencer might say on Instagram or

02:26:32.000 --> 02:26:36.680
[Amit Varma]: YouTube unless that influencer is around the third year and instead sort of think

02:26:36.680 --> 02:26:41.240
[Amit Varma]: a little harder for yourself by the way I'm half Bengali but despite that I like

02:26:41.240 --> 02:26:45.600
[Amit Varma]: the thought of neither poha nor milk nor sugar so that was for a moment I was a

02:26:45.600 --> 02:26:49.440
[Amit Varma]: ghastly thought of a combination now I am reminded by something you said of

02:26:49.440 --> 02:26:54.240
[Amit Varma]: this great book called behave by Robert Sapolsky and and you know the listeners

02:26:54.240 --> 02:26:57.320
[Amit Varma]: who will hark back to the first commercial of this episode will realize

02:26:57.320 --> 02:27:01.480
[Amit Varma]: that I've recommended a course by Sapolsky which is on the great courses

